<HEADLINE> France Denies It Will Boycott D.R. Congo Aid Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- France today denied that it will
boycott the international conference on providing aid to the
Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R. Congo).
</P>
<P>
It is a "completely false" rumor that France will boycott the
meeting that will be held in Brussels Wednesday, said French
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
"It is false to say that France opposes, puts a spoke in the
wheel, boycotts, or is negative in regard to this meeting of
Brussels. It will participate in the meeting," said the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The D.R. Congo expelled last week a first secretary of the
French embassy in Kinshasa, Eric Lubin, for "activities
incompatible with his status." In retaliation, France also
expelled a first secretary of the embassy of D.R. Congo in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Anne Gazeau-Secret said France has no prejudice toward the
D.R. Congo and will listen to the request for aid from the
D.R. Congo government.
</P>
<P>
"We will be as attentive as others to the display of the plan
of the Democratic Republic of Congo and to the analysis of its
need in terms of assistance and proposals of aid for this country
which has been ravaged by a certain number of conflicts in recent
years," said the foreign ministry spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The D.R.Congo government said in a document issued before the
conference that it needs 1.29 billion U.S. dollars, including 728
million dollars of foreign aid, for its "emergency program" of
reconstructing the country which was ruined by the "predatory
power of Marshal Mobutu Sese Seko."
</P>
<P>
The Brussels conference is sponsored by the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
