<HEADLINE> Ceremony Marks Opening of New Railway Project in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony was held in the city
of Xingyi in southwest China's Guizhou province today, to mark the
opening of a new railway line that links the capitals of Guangxi
and Yunnan, both in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng sent a message saying that emphasis should be
placed on safety and punctual, good service, and Vice-premier Zhu
Rongji sent a letter of congratulations.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Zou Jiahua also congratulated builders, scientific
and technical personnel as well as people of various ethnic groups
along the rail route on behalf of the State Council, thanking them
for their work on the country's most technically sophisticated
railway project.
</P>
<P>
The railway will boost economic growth in southwestern China
and further increase the unity of various national minorities, and
called it another milestone in man conquering nature.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders paid a great deal of attention to the progress
of railway construction. Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu Rongji and Zou
Jiahua visited construction sites several times and got directly
involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
The 899.7-km railway runs from Nanning, the capital city of the
southwestern Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, to Kunming, the
capital of Yunnan Province, and has a trunk line to Hongguo in
Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
It cost 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion US dollars), and passes
through perilous mountain areas and crosses torrential rivers,
with an altitude change of more than 2,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
The new railway and the Three Gorges Project constitute part of
a national strategy of tapping the economic potential of central
and western parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiaoxi, a senior economist, said that the central government
plans to inject 600 billion yuan (72.3 billion dollars) to 800
billion yuan (96.4 billion US dollars) into the western part of
the country during the period of the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000), and 43 percent of the state's leading projects will
be there, and a large number of programs financed by foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
Today's ceremony was attended by representatives of the
Ministry of railways, the Ministry of Coal Industry, and the China
Development Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
