<HEADLINE> Pak Senate Chairman Assumes Office of President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Senate Chairman
Wasim Sajjad today assumed the office of president, following the
resignation of President Farooq Leghari.
</P>
<P>
According to the Pakistan Constitution, the 56-year-old Wasim
will act as president until a president is elected within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Wasim, who was born on March 30, 1941, was elected Senate
Chairman four times. Graduated from Punjab University in 1961,
Sajjad had been practicing law at the High Court and the Supreme
Court since 1966 and appeared in a large number of cases of
constitutional and legal importance.
</P>
<P>
He held the cabinet portfolio as federal minister for justice
and parliamentary affairs from September 28, 1986 to December 1,
1988.
</P>
<P>
He acted as president of Pakistan on several occasions during
the absence of the president and also during the critical period
when Ghulam Ishaq Khan vacated the office of president on July 19,
1993 when there was a vacuum of leadership in the country.
</P>
<P>
President Farooq Leghari has formally tendered his resignation
soon
after addressing a news conference here this evening, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The 23-word resignation letter has been sent to Speaker of the
National Assembly Ellahi Soomro, they said, adding Leghari left
his
office for residential quarters of the Presidency immediately
after
signing the letter.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, who assumed his office as president four years ago,
told a
crowded news conference here this evening that he received today a

summary to disqualify Chief Justice Sajjad and appoint the senior
most
judge of the Supreme Court as the next Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing president said he had no option but to sign it.
But,
instead, he decided to quit.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided to resign for the supremacy of the judiciary
and the
constitution of the country," Leghari said, adding an official
announcement of his resignation will be released soon.
</P>
<P>
The nerve-wracking tussle between Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
and
Chief Justice Sajjad reached its climax today when Sajjad
suspended this
morning the 13th amendment to the constitution passed by the two
houses
of Parliament in April, which clipped the presidential power to
dismiss
an elected government.
</P>
<P>
However, minutes after Sajjad's order, a rival 10-member bench
of the
Supreme Court declared his order invalid because he has been under

suspension.
</P>
<P>
Leghari's resignation also came hours after his meeting with
the
powerful Chief of the Army Staff Jahangir Karamat, who has been
acting as
the mediator in the four-month-old confrontation between the
government
and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the Supreme Court issued the conflicting
orders
today, Karamat also met with Prime Minister Sharif earlier in the
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
