<HEADLINE> Defendant: Libya Not Behind 1986 Bombing of Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Defendant Musbah Abulgasem Eter
said today in a Berlin court that Libya was not behind the 1986
bombing of Berlin's La Belle discotheque in which three people
were killed and more than 200 others injured.
</P>
<P>
Revoking alleged confessions, Eter said on the third day of the
trial that he and the four other defendants in the case had not
carried out the attack on the haunt of American military
servicemen, neither had the bombing been backed by the Libyan
embassy in East Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Blaming Libya for the incident, the United States had ordered
air strikes in revenge against Tripoli and Benghazi, causing
dozens of deaths including the adopted daughter of Libyan leader
Moamer Gaddafi.
</P>
<P>
It was alleged that a senior member of the Libyan secret
service in Tripoli had ordered diplomats in East Berlin to carry
out "an attack that would kill as many U.S. military personnel as
possible."
</P>
<P>
Eter, a 40-year-old Libyan diplomat, said that another group
was responsible for the disco bombing on April 5, 1986, which
comprised two Italians and a Libyan who was later murdered.
</P>
<P>
According to him, defendant Verena Chanaa took a bag with only
a dummy bomb inside to the disco, but the bag was later exchanged
with explosives by the above-mentioned group, a move not approved
by the Libyan embassy.
</P>
<P>
In the trial two Palestinians, Yasser Chraidi, 38, Ali Channa,
38, and Ali's ex-wife Verena, 38, are accused of three counts of
murder, nine counts of attempted murder and one count of causing
an explosion. Eter and Verena's sister Andrea Haeusler, 32, are
charged as their accomplices.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said Eter made a detailed statement at the German
embassy in Malta in summer 1996 implicating both his co-defendants
and Libya in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
He was set free after confessing a role in the attack and
helping police solve the case, but he vanished when charges were
preferred and was arrested in Rome in last August.
</P>
<P>
Defending the version he gave in court, Eter said he had not
been correctly understood when questioned by police because of a
bad interpreter.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Eter giving his present testimony, presiding judge
Peter Marhofer said Eter might also be guilty of direct
involvement in the bombing, which would make mitigation unlikely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
