<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, December 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistani President Farooq Leghari said here
today he has decided to resign in order to end the ongoing
constitutional crisis involving the executive and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, who assumed his office four years ago, announced his
resignation hours after his meeting with the powerful Chief of the
Army Staff General Jahangir Karamat, who has been acting as the
mediator in the confrontation between Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
and Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
(Pakistan-President-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said
on Monday that there should be several changes in the procedures
of the U.N. sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf said at today's news conference that it would be
unacceptable for Iraq to accept "the same defects and the same
problems and the same delay practice" as what had happened in the
first and second phases of the implementation of the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the United States for obstructing the approval of
contracts signed by Iraq with other countries under the
oil-for-food program.  (Iraq-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel Knesset (Parliament) on Monday rejected a
motion of no-confidence against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
by a vote of 50 to 45.
</P>
<P>
The motion was tabled by the left wing party Meretz, which
charged that Netanyahu has failed in advancing the Oslo peace
process and there was nothing new in the government decision on
the further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet Sunday approved Netanyahu's proposal that
Israel is to implement further withdrawal from unspecified areas
of the West Bank on condition that Palestinian side fulfills its
commitments under the Hebron Agreement signed last January.
(Israel-Motion-Reject)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
