<HEADLINE> UN to Send Observer Mission to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is expected
to send an observer mission to Sierra Leone, if a report of the
Secretary-General Kofi Annan is approved by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
A report of the News Agency of Nigeria said today that the
drafting of the report is now in progress and is expected to be
completed by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
Work on the report started after the return to New York of two
technical teams sent by the secretary-general to explore ground
for deployment of an observer mission to Sierra Leone, the report
quoted a U.N. secretariat source as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general's report is expected to recommend the
form, size and scope of mandate of the proposed observer mission,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), which
has been brokering for Sierra Leone's return to peace and
democracy since the May 25 coup, demanded in November that the
U.N. sends an observer mission as a form of support to the peace
effort in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sierra Leone's permanent representative to the
U.N., James Jonah, said the disarmament of the Sierra Leonean
army and its ally, the former rebel group of the Revolutionary
United Front will start on December 4, even though the U.N.
observer mission will not be in place by then.
</P>
<P>
Jonah, who is representing the ousted President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah explained that the disarmament is primarily the
responsibility of the ECOWAS peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG,
according to the Conakry agreement signed between ECOWAS and the
Sierra Leonean junta led by Major Paul Johnny Koromah.
</P>
<P>
Besides the disarmament, the agreement also provided for the
restoration of the Kabbah government, the granting of amnesty to
Koromah and his comrades and the resettlement of refugees and
displaced persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
