<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Compensate Jews Robbed by Nazis by Itself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- France will compensate the Jews
robbed by Nazis during World War II in France by itself through
re-distributing the 2.2 tons of gold expected to be returned to
France by what remains of a wartime Allied commission in charge of
recovering gold from Germany after the war.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States today decided to establish an
international fund to compensate the Jews robbed by Nazi Germany
during the war at the conference on the compensation of the Jews
which is being held in London from today until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 337 tons of gold recovered by the Allied countries from
Germany after the war, only 5.5 tons still remain in the bunks of
an Allied tripartite commission in charge of re-distributing the
robbed gold to countries occupied by Germany.
</P>
<P>
France, Britain and the United States are members of the
commission, which was set up in 1946 and is headquartered in
Brussels. The gold recovered by the Allies is kept in the United
States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
When announcing the creation of the fund, British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook said that the remainder of recovered Nazi
gold can be re-distributed to Jews either through the fund in a
multinational way or on a national basis.
</P>
<P>
France claims the right to 2.2 tons of the remaining 5.5 tons
of gold and expects the commission to return them to France within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The French government will then re-distribute these gold to the
families of Nazi victims through the Jewish community in France.
</P>
<P>
A special commission was set up by the former government of
Alain Juppe in February to study how these gold should be returned
to the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
France has not excluded the possibility of contributing to the
international fund for compensating Jews robbed during the war,
while the United States has agreed to contribute 25 million U.S.
dollars and Britain has also agreed to contribute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang: Visit to Strengthen Sino-Mexican Friendship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here today that his current visit to Mexico is intended
to strengthen China-Mexico friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the Mexican Senate, Jiang said he was
here "with the aim of deepening understanding, enhancing
friendship, looking forward to the future and developing
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
He said the people of Mexico, home to the ancient Maya-Azteca
civilization, has won world-wide acclaim for its efforts towards
progress and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang briefed the audience on China's efforts of
reform and opening-up, the resumption of sovereignty over Hong
Kong, and the convening of the 15th National Congress of the
Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
"A more developed China will make greater contributions to the
lofty cause of world peace and development," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said Sino-Mexican friendship dates back to ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Since the 16th century, the Mexican port of Acapulco had
witnessed the frequent visits of merchant ships loaded with
chinaware and silks, opening a magnificent chapter in exchanges
between the two peoples, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
China-Mexico commodity trade further developed in the 18th
century and Mexican silver coins flooded in coastal China,
becoming a currency in wide circulation for a period of time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many Chinese laborers went to Mexico, their number
reaching 30,000 at the start of the 20th century. They contributed
their wisdom and energy to the development of Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
For contemporary China-Mexico relations, Jiang noted the
continuous progress in bilateral exchanges and cooperation in
various fields since the two countries established diplomatic
relations 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Mexican lawmakers for their efforts in
maintaining friendly cooperation with the Chinese National
People's Congress and in deepening understanding and friendship
between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Jiang said, he and his Mexican counterpart,
Ernesto Zedillo, had a profound exchange of views and reached
wide-ranging consensus on bilateral ties and some major
international and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
"We both believe that an all-round China-Mexico partnership is
not only in conformity with the fundamental interests of the two
peoples but also conducive to peace, stability and development in
the Asia-Pacific and the world at large," he added.
</P>
<P>
A number of agreements on bilateral cooperation in consular
affairs, sports, social sciences and economy were also signed
during the visit, consolidating and deepening the friendly
cooperation between the two nations, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is on a five-day state visit to Mexico. He earlier
attended the fifth informal leaders' meeting of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum in Vancouver, Canada and then paid a
four-day state visit to Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
