<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Disabled People Discriminated Against on Job Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Disabled people in Britain are
discriminated against on the job market and most of them remain
unemployed, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
The research by the Royal National Institute for Deaf People
found deafness a bigger obstacle to getting a job than having a
criminal record or a history of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
The study said that 77 percent of those interviewed call
blindness a major obstacle and 64 percent say deafness a major
obstacle.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, having a criminal record scored 61 percent, a
history of drug abuse 60 percent, manic depression 51 percent and
being wheelchair-bound 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
The institute's chief executive James Strachan said that the
vast majority of deaf people want to work, but because of a
combination of complacent employers, unsympathetic colleagues and
redundant legislation, they remain unemployed or, at best,
underemployed.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Labor government has promised tougher
measures to enforce disabled people's rights and is providing 195
million pounds (331.5 million US dollars) under the
welfare-to-work program for pilot schemes to help sick and
disabled people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
