<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WGC Income Forecast to Fall in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The revenues of the World Gold
Council (WGC) is forecast to fall substantially in 1998 due to the
low gold prices, Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The WGC, the only organization promoting internationally the
use of gold, was reported as having decided to reduce the standard
fee by its member company for next year by 30 percent, from 2.50
US dollars for each ounce of gold produced to 1.75 dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, there will be no change in the one dollar an ounce
fees for companies joining the council, the WGC said.
</P>
<P>
The council has also decided to cut its 1998 promotion budget.
</P>
<P>
According to the council's annual report, members' fees stood
at 63.4 million dollars in 1996, compared with 64.1 million in
1995. Voluntary contributions also fell from 3.1 million dollars
to 1.86 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
