<HEADLINE> Greece, Albania Agree to Combat Rising Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The police forces of Greece and
Albania will work together to combat illegal immigrants and
organized crime following an agreement reached here today between
Greek Public Order Minister George Romeos and visiting Albanian
Interior Minister Neritan Ceka.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Romeos said that the two police
forces will cooperate closely in dealing with the mass influx of
Albanians and rising crime in Greece, particularly on the
northwestern island of Corfu.
</P>
<P>
Joint operations have already begun between the two police
forces on some Greek islands as well as along the border between
the two countries and on the Albanian coast, he said. "We are
cooperating more and more closely," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ceka described the cooperation between the two
police forces as being "at an excellent level," saying that they
will work closely with the Greek side to tackle the illegal
activities by Albanians. 
</P>
