<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Constitutional Crisis Takes New Turn with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The worst ever constitutional
crisis in Pakistan has taken a new twist as President Farooq
Leghari resigned today from his office.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, the eighth president of Pakistan since the country's
independence in August 1947, formally tendered his resignation
this evening after refusing to sign a reference against Chief
Justice Sajjad Ali Shah as recommended by the government of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, who assumed his office four years ago, announced his
decision at a crowded press conference held at the Presidential
House earlier this evening.
</P>
<P>
He said that he received a summary from the government that he
should disqualify the Chief Justice and appoint Justice Ajmal Mian
as acting Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
"The President has no option but to sign such summary. But I
will not exercise that option because I hold certain principles
above self- interest. And therefore I have decided to resign,"
Leghari said.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of President Leghari came amid a political and
constitutional deadlock which gripped the country a week ago with
Chief Justice Sajjad and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif at the center
stage.
</P>
<P>
During the four-month-old crisis, the out-going president
seemed to have been sandwiched between the warring government with
a heavy mandate and an aggressive Chief Justice Sajjad whose
authority was lately challenged by a majority of his own
colleagues on the bench.
</P>
<P>
The nerve-wracking tussle between Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
and Chief Justice Sajjad reached its climax today when Sajjad
suspended this morning the 13th amendment to the constitution
passed by Parliament in April, which clipped the presidential
power to dismiss an elected government.
</P>
<P>
However, minutes after Sajjad's order, a rival 10-member bench
of the Supreme Court declared his order invalid on the ground that
he has been suspended.
</P>
<P>
Hours after Leghari's stepping down, Senate Chairman Wasim
Sajjad this evening assumed the charge of acting president till
the election of Leghari's successor by the two houses of
parliament and four provincial assemblies within 30 days as
provided in the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Experts here noted that the next president from the ruling
party would help government get rid of the estranged Chief Justice
who has also lost support of the majority of his colleagues in the
apex court.
</P>
<P>
However, Sajjad's aide made it clear in a telephone interview
that the Chief Justice is not prepared to resign and will attend
the court on Wednesday as usual.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest developments, Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain said "it was a victory of democracy, institutions
and principles of parliamentary sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
"The Army played a very positive role in stabilizing the
situation and I feel it is a sign of maturity in Pakistan's
political system," he said.
</P>
<P>
The President's resignation has already triggered heavy buying
activity at the Karachi stock market, which has remained under
severe depression during the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The 100-Index of Karachi Stock Exchange closed up 2.04 points
to 1789.22, dealers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Makes Contribution to Holocaust Victim Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has pledged to
contribute an immediate 4 million U.S. dollars to the
international fund for Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the international conference on Nazi gold opening in
London this morning, U.S. Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat
made the announcement of the U.S. contribution.
</P>
<P>
"I want to announce the decision of the United States
government to deposit 4 million dollars in the fund as a
down-payment," Eizenstat said.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that the total U.S. contribution to the fund
will be increased to 25 million dollars over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who
formally announced the establishment of the international fund to
be based in New York, said that the British government will
contribute 1 million pounds (about 1.7 million dollars) to the
fund.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day conference, representatives from over 40
countries and non-government organizations would focus on where
the Nazi gold came from, what happened to it and what steps taken
to compensate victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
