<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Foreign Debts Stand at 29.9 b Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran's total foreign debts
stood at 29.9 billion U.S. dollars in last June, local daily Salam
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a report from the Central Bank of Iran (CBI), the
daily said that the figure also included foreign commitments which
were signed with foreign countries but were not implemented so far.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the confirmed foreign debts until June
was 15.836 billion dollars, about 1 billion less than the figure
by March 20, the end of last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the due foreign debts would be 4.902 billion
dollars in the coming Iranian year beginning on March 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the country's trade, the report said that the
country's total oil and non-oil exports were valued at 22.496
billion dollars and its total imports 14.973 billion dollars in
last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of the current Iranian year, the
country's exports reached 4.861 billion dollars while its imports
were 3.992 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In October, CBI Governor Mohsen Nourbakhsh announced that the
bank has paid off 75 percent of its arrears and only 3.6 billion
dollars has remained from Iran's total rescheduled debts which
should be paid next year.
</P>
<P>
Iran was hit by sharp oil price falls in the world markets in
1993 and was forced to reschedule its overdue foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, higher oil prices and stringent
economic measures helped ease the pressure of foreign debt on the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
