<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR to Stay at Present Force Level Till Next June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led multinational
Stabilization Force (SFOR) will stay in Bosnia at the current
force level until the end of its peace-keeping mandate, NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana said today.
</P>
<P>
But the Western military alliance did not make any decision on
whether and how to maintain a military presence in the former
Yugoslav republic beyond June next year though an initial exchange
of views was made at the NATO defense ministers meeting on the
possibility of a follow-on force to consolidate the peace
implementation process.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Council will have to consult non-NATO
contributing countries to the SFOR before the final decision is
taken after the peace implementation conference and the NATO
foreign ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
The peace implementation conference will be held next Monday
and Tuesday while the foreign ministers meeting is slated for the
week after.
</P>
<P>
A number of questions remained to be answered before NATO makes
its decision on its future role in Bosnia, said Solana at a
post-defense ministers meeting press conference.
</P>
<P>
NATO has tasked the North Atlantic Council, the executive body
of the 16-nation alliance, to develop a political-military
guidance for the NATO military authorities to consider a range of
options for a possible follow-on force after the SFOR's mandate.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs of defense from the 16 NATO member states reviewed
the 12-month point of the SFOR's mission in Bosnia and all
ministers underscored the outstanding job the SFOR is doing as
Solana put it.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said that the SFOR has provided vital support to
key civil implementation activities such as the municipal
elections, the parliamentary elections of the Republika Srpska and
the restructuring of the Bosnian media and police.
</P>
<P>
But the NATO chief said that much more has to be achieved
before peace can be truly self-sustaining in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO has planned a phase-out withdrawal of the SFOR troops, now
at 34,000, for the post-election period leading up to next June
when the peace-keeping mission expires.
</P>
<P>
United States Defense Secretary William Cohen said that U.S.
President Bill Clinton made no decision on the U.S. participation
in the post-mandate military presence in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has to justify the new mission after considering issues
such as national interest, cost, military morale and how-to, said
Cohen at another press briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are in favor of resorting to police forces to
keep Bosnia in order.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. defense secretary urged the European allies of NATO to
contribute more to training the police force in that the Americans
are making a financial contribution to the International Police
Task Force in Bosnia with a ratio of 5-1, according to Cohen.
</P>
<P>
What in need is a highly efficient and well-trained police
force in Bosnia to avoid a permanent military presence in the
Balkan country, said the U.S. defense secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
