<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Movement Pushes for Israeli Pullback From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli peace movement
today pressed ahead with its call for a unilateral Israeli troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon, where it is bogged down in a brute
guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference here, opposition lawmaker and
former senior minister, Yossi Beilin, who recently formed the
Movement for a Peaceful Departure from Lebanon (MPDL), outlined
his group's plan for Israel's unilateral withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The MPDL based its proposal on two principles: Israeli troops
pull back to the internationally border in accordance with
U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 and Israel takes necessary
steps to ensure maximal security of its residents along the
northern border.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said his movement proposed a timetable for the
withdrawal from Israel's self-styled security zone in south
Lebanon within six months after proper preparations for better
defense of its northern border are made.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out the 10-15 kilometer wide strip along the
border to buffer attacks from Islamic militants who vowed to fight
till the end of Israeli occupation of the area. The zone is
patrolled by 1,200 Israeli troops and 3,000 South Lebanon Army
which is trained and armed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said the arrangements include ensuring the well-being of
the South Lebanese Army, which helped Israel combat Hezbollah
guerrillas, after Israel's departure, and setting up electronic
fence, military outposts, minefields and patrol along the border.
</P>
<P>
During the period of troop redeployment, he said, Israel should
make serious efforts to reach agreements and understanding with
Lebanese government, whose troops will be asked to take
responsibility in south Lebanon, according to his plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel must make clear to Syria and Iran, believed
to be the major supporters of the Hezbollah guerrilla force, that
Israel will hold them responsible for any cross-border attack
against Israel after the withdrawal, Beilin said.
</P>
<P>
If attacked from across the border, Israel retains the freedom
to act in any place and with any means, including returning to
south Lebanon, to secure the safety of its northern residents.
</P>
<P>
Islamic resistance forces of Lebanon have been fighting to
drive the Israelis out of the area, where the armed clashes have
caused heavy casualties to Israeli soldiers every year.
</P>
<P>
This fueled heated debates in Israel over the need of getting
out of south Lebanon voluntarily since the so-called security zone
has become a death trap.
</P>
<P>
Beilin contended that with the redeployment, Israel will free
itself from the quagmire in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his movement has gained popular support since
its founding among various sectors of the society. Its 3,400
members include lawmakers from both the ruling coalition and the
opposition, activists of the left and the right.
</P>
<P>
The death toll of Israeli soldiers has risen to 112 since the
beginning of this year, including 73 killed in a collision of two
transport helicopters near the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
