<HEADLINE> SPD Confident in Taking Over Power After 1998 Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOVER, Germany, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Oskar Lafontaine,
leader of Germany's main opposition Social Democrats (SPD), today
voiced firm confidence about the prospects for his party to win
the 1998 elections after 15 years out of power.
</P>
<P>
"Today we can say we are back: we are the future governing
party of Germany," he said while addressing the three-day SPD
convention beginning today.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine, who is the premier of Saar state, was reelected SPD
chairman at the meeting today with 463 "yes" votes out of 499
ballots cast. He became SPD leader two years ago and has been
praised for rebuilding the party's shattered unity.
</P>
<P>
The SPD lost the last four elections to Chancellor Helmut Kohl
of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), who is seeking a
consecutive fifth term.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls show that the SPD, in a leftist coalition with
the environmentalist Greens Party, could defeat Kohl's
center-right government if a vote were held currently.
</P>
<P>
However, the SPD has not yet decided on its candidate for the
September 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine, badly beaten by Kohl in 1990, wants another chance
while Gerhard Schroeder, SPD premier of Lower Saxony state, is
also seeking the candidacy.
</P>
<P>
They have agreed to ban all discussion on the issue until after
Lower Saxony state elections next March. Schroeder has said he
will give up if he loses more than 2 percent of support in the
state election.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder is more popular outside the SPD and known for his
more conservative, pro-industry views, while Lafontaine is a
traditional supporter of Germany's elaborate social welfare state.
</P>
<P>
Lafontaine criticized in his speech today the Kohl government's
reform efforts to reduce sick-pay and loosen restrictions on
companies' dismissing employees.
</P>
<P>
He meanwhile reiterated the SPD support for the strengthened
role of the European Union in reducing the record 20 million
unemployment in EU countries. He added that the SPD wanted to cut
short working week hours in order to create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder is scheduled to address the SPD convention Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
