<HEADLINE> Israel Warns Arafat Against Statehood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel today warned that
Palestinian declaration of independence will lead to Israeli
unilateral steps to annex part of the occupied territories in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
If Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat unilaterally declares an
independent Palestinian state, Israel will announce annexation of
the Jordan Valley and other territories, said Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu during a talk with coalition partner
Tsomet lawmaker Eliezer Zanberg Monday night, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that he will not act to annex Jordan Valley now
for fear of violating the signed agreements, which call for the
settlement of the final status of the occupied territories through
talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel will not freeze the construction of
settlements, because settlements "are proper and legitimate" even
according to the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai told
reporters today that Israel has the capability to take unilateral
steps if Arafat declares an independent state.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to elaborate measures Israel might take in case
of a Palestinian declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis were responding Arafat's remarks that if Israel
fails to honor its commitments to the Oslo accords, an independent
Palestinian state will be declared by the end of the process in
mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Israeli threats, Arafat said today at a joint news
conference with visiting Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali that a Palestinian state already exists, and what he hopes
only is that its capital will be Jerusalem. 
</P>
