<HEADLINE> IOC Sticks to Sex Test for Women Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The random sex test for women
athletes will be carried forward by the International Olympic
Committee despite waves of calls to scrape the current gender
testing, authorities reaffirmed in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The IOC officials fear that it will be impossible to hold
separate events for men and women in the future if the sex of an
athlete is not tested strictly.
</P>
<P>
IOC medical chief Prince Alexandre de Merode reaffirmed on
Wednesday that Olympic chiefs were not ready to change their minds
on the controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need to change. The majority of people in the IOC
want it to stay," de Merode said after an IOC meeting here.
</P>
<P>
However, IOC doping expert Arne Ljungqvist recommended to end
the chromosome test for all female athletes since the 1968 Mexico
City Olympics because it has been outdated by rapid advances in
genetics.
</P>
<P>
Ljungqvist, a senior member of the International Amateur
Athletic Federation (IAAF), said the test is not useful because
there are men with chromosomes like women and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
He said the IAAF abandoned gender testing in 1992, followed
suit by the Commonwealth and World University Games, and only five
of 34 Olympic federations still conducted gender tests at their
own world championships.
</P>
<P>
IOC officials said the debate has come about because of the
major legal problems in Norway in forcing women to take sex tests.
</P>
<P>
Currently, testers analyse cells scraped from the inside of the
cheek to determine the sex of an athlete.
</P>
<P>
About one in 400 females in Atlanta tested male but all were
cleared by subsequent physical examinations.
</P>
<P>
However, physical examinations will cause problems with an
invasion of privacy in such routine examinations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
