<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Court Upholds Ruling on Oil Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Supreme Court
today upheld its earlier decision to nullify the country's
nine-month oil deregulation law.
</P>
<P>
In the court's resolution, the motions filed by the Office of
the Solicitor General and five oil firms for reconsideration of
the court original ruling were denied for lack of merit.
</P>
<P>
The court struck down the law as unconstitutional again, saying
some of its provisions violated the constitutional prohibition of
monopolies and unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
The court said it is its "unyielding duty to uphold the
supremacy of the constitution, which provides a shield to the
economic rights of the Filipino people especially the poor."
</P>
<P>
With this finality, the oil industry will now go back to
government control after about nine months of free market play.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil deregulation law, which ended 20 years of
government control of the oil industry, the government withdrew
its huge subsidy to the industry and the country's three main oil
firms can adjust oil prices freely.
</P>
<P>
The court ruling has generated widespread concerns among the
government and the business community, which feared it could
worsen the country's already-gloomy economic situation and scare
away investors.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos has urged the Congress to pass a new oil
deregulation law to strengthen investors' confidence in the
country's economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SPD Approves German Participation in UN Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOVER, Germany, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main
opposition Social Democrats (SPD) today proposed that Bonn should
establish stand-by troops aimed at taking part in United Nations
peacekeeping operations.
</P>
<P>
The SPD approved the German participation in UN peacekeeping
operations at a three-day party convention that opened Tuesday in
Hanover.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution the SPD confirmed UN blue helmet missions under
certain conditions as "a successful instrument to secure peace
either prior to or after hostilities."
</P>
<P>
It meanwhile suggested a reduction in the 340,000-strong German
armed forces, the Bundeswehr. Without specifying the cuts, it
rejected a proposal to reduce the Bundeswehr to 150,000.
</P>
<P>
The SPD also warned that the Western military alliance North
Atlantic Treaty Organization should not become a global
intervention instrument.
</P>
<P>
Except for defense of the its 16 member nations, NATO must not
be allowed to involve in any operations without approval from the
UN or the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe,
said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The SPD also urged the United States to give Europe a bigger
say in the NATO command structure.
</P>
<P>
Expressing support for the NATO eastward expansion, the SPD
however stressed its opposition to any upgrading of the armed
forces in former East Bloc countries.
</P>
<P>
It views the NATO enlargement as an opportunity to reduce the
conventional forces in Europe, according to the resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
