<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspection Continues in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. arms inspection in
Iraq entered its 12th consecutive day today since the weapons
experts were allowed to return and resume work in Baghdad late
last month. No incidents were reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Iraqi News Agency, 11 inspection
teams of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, today set out for declared and
sudden visits to Iraqi industrial, trade and scientific sites.
</P>
<P>
Hussan Mohammed Ameen, director general of Iraqi National
Monitoring Department, the Iraqi counterpart of UNSCOM, said the
Iraqis have been very cooperative, with no delays or problems
reported.
</P>
<P>
Two groups were helicoptered to inspect suspected weapons
sites, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iraq's "credibility and cooperation" lay bare the
"false U.S. allegations which aim to maintain the embargo on Iraqi
people and represent a deliberate flagrant violation of human
rights."
</P>
<P>
On October 29, Baghdad threatened to expel American inspectors
on the UNSCOM team on charges of spying and hindering the lifting
of the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions against Iraq, setting off an
Iraq-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
Since returning to Baghdad on November 21, U.N. arms inspectors
have steered clear of "sensitive" areas - presidential palaces
which the Iraqis say are signs of national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Head of UNSCOM, Richard Butler, will visit Baghdad at the end
of this week in a bid to persuade Iraq to allow inspectors into
those "off-limits" sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
