<HEADLINE> Shanghai Holds Symposium On Modern-Day Job-Related Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and American experts
today attended a symposium in Shanghai today to discuss problems
suffered by professional people in their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
Liang Youxin, a professor with Shanghai Medical Sciences
University, said that more Chinese wage-earners are suffering from
nervous disorders and other problems brought on by job insecurity,
stress, competition, and relationships between people.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes more research in the field of professional
stress problems will greatly benefit Chinese economic development
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Starting in the 1950s, China began establishing health services
or clinics at most state-run enterprises, and recent studies have
shown that the incidence of job-related illnesses saw a drop in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China increased exchanges and co-operation
with international public health organizations. 
</P>
