<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Language Unpopular in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The official language of Ukraine,
which is Ukrainian, remains unpopular in many areas despite
efforts by the government to encourage its use, the Ukrainian News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian language is more widespread than the official
language in the areas of science, technology, business and
sports," the report quoted Deputy Prime Minister Valeri Smoly as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Smoly added that some government organs tended to ignore the
Ukrainian language instead of using it. He referred to the
parliament of the Crimean Republic which recently adopted a law
declaring Russian the official and business language in the
autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Russian, regarded as a minority language in Ukraine, is the
most common tongue in both everyday life and the scientific
community. Even Ukrainian President Lenoid Kuchma is reported to
be much more fluent in Russian than in Ukrainian.
</P>
<P>
"All the Ukrainian residents are brought up with poems by
Pushkin, but it has suddenly become foreign literature," said
Vasyl Minolovich, a teacher in a Kiev driving school. "It's
extremely ridiculous and sad if you think about it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
