<HEADLINE> Afghan Women Ask Return of Legitimate Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan women, who have
endured tremendous hardships, demand restoration of their
legitimate rights, head of the Afghan Women Organization Khadija
Balkhi said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference on Afghan peace in Iran's central city
of Isfahan, Balkhi said "The Muslim women of Afghanistan only seek
to restore their legitimate, civil rights and have no ambitions
for government posts."
</P>
<P>
According to the official new agency IRNA, the three-day
conference opened Monday were attended by hundreds of famous
political, religious and military figures of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Condemning the continued bloodshed in the war-torn country,
Balkhi said "the people seeking to strip the Afghan women of
their legitimate rights are opposed to the prevalence of Islamic
rule in the society."
</P>
<P>
She called on leaders of Afghan factions to cease hostilities
and think about the fate and miseries of homeless Afghans.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday night, exiled Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani told
the conference that a comprehensive peace in Afghanistan could be
achieved only through the help by all countries, specially Muslim
states, as well as the Organization of the Islamic Conference and
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
All individuals and groups in Afghanistan, even the Taliban
which fought into Kabul and seized power more than a year ago,
should participate in the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the anti-Taliban United Front has no opposition to
peace and at the same time does not insist on monopolizing power
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said that any decision reached through negotiations
would be acceptable to the United Front, but any attempt to
disintegrate the country would face defeat.
</P>
<P>
He expressed support to the proposal for holding a peace
conference on Afghanistan, hoping that all the groups would
participate in the conference.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the conference today, head of the Afghan National
Understanding Council Pir Seyed Gilani called for identification
and trial of war criminals in Afghanistan by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Gilani said he supports the proposal to form a fund by the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) in order to help the
Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
He said the aid collected at the OIC summit should be offered
to the U.N. bureau in Afghanistan as well as the Afghan refugee
camps based in Iran and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Iran's representative to the meeting Alaeddin Boroujerdi on
Tuesday blasted the Taliban for its absence in the Isfahan
conference, saying this indicated that the group was not for peace
and stability in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
