<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Adopts Amnesty Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma, the lower
house of parliament, today passed in the first reading a draft
resolution on amnesty for 435,000 prisoners, including 35,000
serving sentences in detention facilities, according to the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Duma is to vote on the resolution in three hearings. The
document does not require voting in the Federation Council. It
takes effect on the day it is made public.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution, those eligible for amnesty are people of
pension age, mothers of young children, pregnant women and
patients with tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov said on Tuesday that the amnesty
is not applicable to persons convicted for murder, rape, bandit
attacks and other heinous crimes.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, president Boris Yeltsin sent a letter to the
Duma explaining that the amnesty was needed "not only for
considerations of humaneness," but because of extremely scarce
budget donations to Russian jails. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
