<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Real GDP Grows 0.8 Percent in July-September Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan's seasonally adjusted gross
domestic product (GDP) grew 0.8 percent in the July-September
period from the previous quarter, an annualized rate of 3.1
percent, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said in a report today.
</P>
<P>
The GDP for the April-June period shrank at a revised annual
rate of 10.6 percent, the biggest contraction rate in 23 years,
because of a decline in personal spending following the
consumption tax hike from 3 to 5 percent on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Japan's July-September GDP totaled an annualized 483,209.6
billion yen (about 3.766 trillion U.S. dollars) after adjustment
for inflation and seasonal factors, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demand pushed up Japan's GDP for the period by 0.9
percentage point as the negative impact of the consumption tax
hike faded, while external demand reduced GDP growth by a negative
0.1 percentage point.
</P>
<P>
Among GDP components, personal consumption, which accounts for
about 60 percent of the GDP aggregate, rose 1.6 percent in the
period from the previous quarter, the EPA said, adding that
corporate capital spending, another engine of the economy, also
marked a 1.6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment declined 10.5 percent from the previous
quarter, marking the third consecutive quarterly fall, but public
investment posted a 1.3 percent rise, following a 0.5 percent
increase in the April-June quarter.
</P>
<P>
The GDP deflator, the key inflation gauge, rose 0.9 percent,
following a 0.7 percent increase in the previous period, the EPA
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the report, Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka said that he finally sees a "bright sign" for the future
course of the economy through the 0.8 percent growth in GDP.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate is an indication of economic recovery, but the
government will keep a close watch on the economy, Mitsuzuka said.
</P>
<P>
Private-sector analysts, however, said the data indicates that the
economy has entered a recessional phase, noting the recovery in
personal consumption is still sluggish. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
