<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Leghari's Exit, High Cost for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The worst ever constitutional
crisis in the history of Pakistan has taken a new turn when Farooq
Leghari stepped down from the presidency Tuesday with almost one
year of his five-year term still to go.
</P>
<P>
It is by no means an unexpected development to many of those
who were following closely the political crisis that an epic
tussle between the executive and the judiciary has finally taken
its toll in the resignation of Leghari as head of the state and
actual exit of Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah.
</P>
<P>
It may well be seen as a high cost for a solution of the
constitutional crisis which has been gripping this South Asian
nation for almost four months.
</P>
<P>
The day of December 2, 1997 attracted worldwide attention as
the four-month-old nerve-wracking constitutional crisis reached
its climax.
</P>
<P>
The uncertainty in the political landscape of Pakistan was
created Tuesday morning by the issuance of two cause lists by the
two opposing groups in the country's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
A three-member bench led by Chief Justice Sajjad suspended the
13th Amendment to the Constitution which was passed by the two
Houses of Parliament in April this year to deprive the president
of the powers to dissolve the National Assembly and to dismiss the
government.
</P>
<P>
As a counterattack, a rival 10-member bench of the apex court
issued an order a few minutes later that the ruling by the
three-member bench was invalid on the ground that the appointment
of the chief justice had already been suspended by the Quetta and
Peshawar benches of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented high drama in a divided apex court made the
already chaotic political situation more complicated.
</P>
<P>
Speculations and rumors like the dissolvement of the National
Assembly and impeachment of the president were being spread in the
capital city. Although people here had been caught in an agonizing
game of guessing as what was going to happen, every one was
certain, however, that the situation in the country was not to the
benefit of any one.
</P>
<P>
Farooq Leghari said at a press conference late Tuesday
afternoon that the whole crisis was "self-created", "unnecessary"
and "hurtful" to the country.
</P>
<P>
Leghari, the eighth president who formally tendered his
resignation since the inception of Pakistan half a century a go,
believed that the political crisis could have been avoided had the
government listened to his advises during the whole process.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that Leghari, who assumed his presidency in
November 1993, had been sandwiched between the warring government
with a heavy mandate and an aggressive chief justice whose
authority has been challenged by a majority of his own colleagues
in the court.
</P>
<P>
The immediate reason for Leghari's resignation seems to be a
government demand that he sign a notice which would have
discharged Chief Justice Shah and replaced him by most senior
judge of the apex court Ajmal Mian.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here are of the view that the actual reason
for Leghari's exit is more than that. The resignation of the
president itself indicated the depth of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Now, Pakistan has again an acting president and at the same
time an acting Chief Justice -- a scenario which is nothing new to
the Pakistani people who have experienced ups and downs in the
country's politics during the last few decades.
</P>
<P>
It may be said that Leghari's exit came as a big relief to the
government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who is facing charges
on the Contempt of Court.
</P>
<P>
However, it would be premature to believe that the
constitutional crisis is over as the loss done to the country's
economy and the judiciary cannot be restored in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
