<HEADLINE> Japan's Administrative Reform Panel Unveils Final Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government's
administrative reform panel today released a final report of
recommendations for streamlining the country's bureaucracy that
skirted crucial reforms of the Finance Ministry under pressure
from the ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
The report, drawn up by the Administrative Reform Council
headed by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, centers on
reorganization of government ministries and agencies to build a
"more simple, efficient and transparent" government.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting an agreement by Japan's ruling parties to postpone a
decision on the issue of whether to strip the Finance Ministry of
its money market-related functions, the report made no reference
to specific functions of a reorganized Treasury Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The final report laid out a rough blueprint of a new
administrative system for the next century under which Japan's
current 22 government ministries and agencies will be reorganized
into 13.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to start preparations for the
reorganization after the cabinet gives the green light to the
proposal at a special session Thursday morning, Sadatoshi Ozato,
head of the Management and Coordination Agency and acting chairman
of the panel, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The government will decide on fundamental principles of
administrative reform by the end of this year and submit a bill to
the Diet (parliament) around mid-March next year with a view to
launching the new system in January 2001, government officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese business leaders welcomed the report, saying it is
significant as it presents measures to enhance the power of the
prime minister and the cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
