<HEADLINE> Pele Predicts Brazil to Win Fifth World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Soccer legend Pele predicted on
Wednesday that Brazil will win its fifth World Cup although the
European teams will dominate the finals next year.
</P>
<P>
"I can see Germany, France, Spain, Italy and perhaps England
contending the semi-final places along with Brazil," said Pele.
</P>
<P>
In 1958, Pele won the first of his three World Cups as a
17-year-old when Brazil became the only country to win the
tournament outside its own continent.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the eight quarter-finalists in 1994 were the European
sides, but Brazil eventually took the unprecedented fourth title.
</P>
<P>
"Neither Germany nor Italy are playing well now but they always
seem to get it right on the day," he said.
</P>
<P>
For Brazil, its biggest problem was the fact it has only played
friendly matches since its victory in the United States, apart
from the 1996 Copa America.
</P>
<P>
Besides, coach Mario Zagallo, who played alongwith Pele in the
1958 and 1962 World Cups, has not decided on his defence and
midfield, said Pele.
</P>
<P>
In his view, South Africa and Yugoslavia could spring a
surprise in the World Cup, saying "I just have the feeling South
Africa could do a Cameroon."
</P>
<P>
In 1990, Roger Milla led Cameroon to a marvellous quarter-final
defeat against England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
