<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Economy Gathers Pace in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian economy picked
up a fair bit of momentum in the third quarter while still
managing to keep a lid on inflation, according to data posted
today by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS).
</P>
<P>
Economists said lifts in private sector expenditure and
dwelling construction had helped support an expansion in the real
average measure of gross domestic product, or GDP, of 1.5 percent
in the quarter and 3.6 percent over the year to September.
</P>
<P>
The outcome was above the median market forecast of a rise of
1.1 percent in the quarter and 3.4 percent over the year, and the
strongest in the series since September quarter 1995.
</P>
<P>
As well, the June quarter GDP result was revised upwards to 1.4
percent, compared to 1.2 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
The ABS said also that the implicit price deflator for GDP,
which is a broad indicator of price pressures, fell 0.1 percent in
the quarter -- its first fall since June 1994. Over the year it
was up 1.7 percent, almost mirroring the underlying inflation
measure monitored by the Reserve Bank of Australia.
</P>
<P>
But a shadow remains over the outlook for the economy into
1998, with a fall back in growth in Asian economies certain to
have a negative impact.
</P>
<P>
"As we go into 1998 we don't think it will be all smooth
sailing and that momentum will be interrupted, firstly, by the
Asian impact and, secondly, by still subdued employment growth,"
said senior economist Peter Osborne.
</P>
<P>
"The growth in private consumption we saw in quarter three will
not be sustained unless we see a clear pick-up in employment from
here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank economist Nigel Stapledon said that today's data
in any case support a no-change monetary policy stance by the
Reserve Bank of Australia. The central bank has remained quiet on
policy since it cut the cash rate to 5.0 percent in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
But Stapledon held that a rate cut in 1998 could not be ruled
out completely.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
