<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Soldiers Killed in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Military sources in the
diamond-rich Kono District in the eastern Sierra Leone claimed
that Kamajor militiamen launched an ambush Tuesday in which four
soldiers and a 24-year woman, Nester Lewis died.
</P>
<P>
Kamajor casualty was not reported in the shoot out. Kamajors
are militiamen which backed president T. Kabbah whose civilian
government was toppled in a May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
And west African countries last month signed a Conakry peace
agreement with the military junta in which the latter promised to
restore the Kabbah regime next April and start disarming all
forces beginning in December in the country in exchange for an
amnesty.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, fighting took place when a convoy of
a member of the military government's Supreme Council of State,
George Adams was ambushed along the strategic Kono-Tongo highway.
</P>
<P>
A Kamajor detachment allegedly opened automatic fire on the
three vehicles and many of the passengers abandoned the cars and
fled into the bush. Adams walked some 12 miles to safety.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors combed the area after the attack and rounded up
four soldiers and reportedly asked for diamonds, resulting in
killing the four soldiers.
</P>
<P>
In Freetown today, the military government accused Kamajors of
killing at random during the ambush, saying, "it violates the
Conakry peace plan which called for an immediate cessation of
hostilities by all sides in the Sierra Leone conflict."
</P>
<P>
However, the Kamajor high command in Kenema today denied it
had anything to do with the recent spate of bloody attacks and
ambushes in the southeastern region of the country.
</P>
<P>
At least some 50 civilians and 20 soldiers have died in recent
clashes in which the military claimed that over 90 Kamajors have
also lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
Yet a Kamajor spokesman told Xinhua, "we are only defending
ourselves."
</P>
<P>
Some people say the military junta has tried to use the ambush
and other clashes with Kamajors as an excuse to refuse to be
disarmed in accordance with the Conakry agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
