<HEADLINE> Chairwoman of Chinese Kuomintang Speaks about Reunification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 2 (Xinhua) -- He Luli, chairwoman of the
Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang (RCCK), said
recently in Beijing that she will try her best to work for a
prosperous and reunified China.
</P>
<P>
He Luli has been involved in politics for 13 years and is a
vice-chairwoman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC). At the recent Ninth
RCCK National Congress, she was re-elected chairwoman of the RCCK,
which was formed in 1948.
</P>
<P>
When she was young she wanted to be a doctor and studied at
Beijing Medical University and still has quite strong feelings
about her old profession. But, like many other people in the past,
she complied with the demands of the country and was elected
deputy head of the Xicheng District of Beijing in 1984, and after
1988, was elected vice-mayor of Beijing Municipality twice.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, I'd prefer to be a paediatrician if I had the choice
again," she told Xinhua in a recent interview, because the
profession had taught her a sense of responsibility, but her
pragmatic work style and political achievements won her the praise
of Beijing's citizens.
</P>
<P>
She was born into a Sino-French family and speaks both English
and French. Her father, He Siyuan, studied in the United States,
Germany and France, and was mayor of Beiping (Beijing) under
Kuomintang rule. Her mother is French.
</P>
<P>
The reunification of the motherland is the common aspiration of
all the Chinese, including the Taiwan compatriots, and a wish of
Dr. Sun Yat-sen, the great forerunner of the Chinese democratic
revolution, she said, expressing the hope that far-sighted
Kuomintang members in Taiwan will adhere to Sun's unfulfilled wish
and make a contribution to the reunification.  
</P>
</TEXT>
