<HEADLINE> Ghana Expects Bumper Cocoa Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Cocoa growers in Ghana, one of
the world's leading cocoa producing countries, are looking
forward to a bumper harvest this year.
</P>
<P>
They say the weather is favorable for the 1997-98
(October-September) crop, forecast to reach between 350,000 and
400,000 tons, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
"There has been enough rain and after the rain the weather has
been glorious in terms of drying," one village chief in Ghana's
key western district on the border with Cote d'Ivoire was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"For all the problems, this year's harvest will be better than
last year," he said, referring to delays in cocoa payments and
higher pesticide costs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Agriculture has forecast Ghana's
1997-98 crop at 350,000 tons after 324,000 tons in the previous
season. Local buyers have said the total could be as high as
400,000 tons, closer to the 1995-96 level.
</P>
<P>
The report also attributed the good harvest to the renewed
enthusiasm of farmers who were given a boost by Ghana's decision
to raise its cocoa price by 50 percent for this year to 1.8
million cedis a ton, making farm maintenance more worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
But farmers at western district continued to complain of
financial problems after the government doubled the price of
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
They also complain of being paid up to 10 weeks late by buying
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
