<HEADLINE> China To Salvage Warship Sunk During Anti-Japanese War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua)-- China plans to raise a warship
sunk by the Japanese navy just over a hundred years ago in the
Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
The "Zhiyuan" was found in waters off Liaoning Province along
with three other warships, and salvage plans are being worked
out. It was involved in a fight against invading Japanese warships
in 1894 and was sunk by torpedoes as it headed for a Japanese
warship in a suicidal dash after it had run out of ammunition. The
captain and 700 sailors died in the battle.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Japanese War of 1894-1895 is regarded as an
humiliating event for China because it was defeated by Japan and
also forced to accept a series of unequal treaties and to pay
large amounts of reparation.
</P>
<P>
Yu Weichao, curator of the Chinese History Museum, views the
salvage work as significant because the ship is historic evidence
of the Japanese invasion and of the weak and corrupt government of
the Qing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xushang, a former deputy commander of the Chinese navy
who is in charge of the salvage operation, said the salvage and
the accompanying memorial to be built can give a sense of
patriotism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
