<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Union Launches Nation-Wide Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Trade Union started
this morning an open-ended general strike in protest against
government plans for wages reform and privatization, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that some 700,000 workers took part in the
strike, which paralyzed large sectors of national economy. Most of
government offices and companies were shut down as well as offices
of municipalities and local authorities. Hospitals, the
telecommunications sector, banks, post offices and other services
were also affected.
</P>
<P>
The strike is the latest round in a Trade Union battle against
government economic reform plans, which have sparked fears that
worker's rights would be harmed.
</P>
<P>
Some 150,000 clerks and municipal workers launched a two-day
strike on last Sunday against cost-cutting measures taken by local
authorities and they resumed work only after the National Labor
Court issued a back-to-work order.
</P>
<P>
Today's strike was trigged by the words of Israeli Finance
Minister Yaakov Neeman on Monday describing the striking workers
as "exploding bombs" and enemies from within.
</P>
<P>
In response to Neeman's assault, Trade Union Chairman Amir
Peretz Tuesday declared the strike at an emergency gathering of
thousands of union members in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman has called for a resolution for
the dispute between the Treasury and the Trade Union in order to
"prevent the collapse of the economy and services." Israeli
Manufacture Association estimated the damage from today's strike
at 53 million shekels (about 15 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a parallel development, the National Labor Court is
considering the government's request to issue back-to-work order
to the striking unions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
