<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Drops Again on Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar today
continued its downward spiral to hit a new four-year low, with
anxiety over the Asian currency crisis swamping
stronger-than-expected national accounts data.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed the session at 67.52 U.S. cents from
67.83 U.S. cents locally late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Intra-day it fell to 67.35 U.S. cents, the lowest level since
December 1993.
</P>
<P>
The local currency had strengthened mid-session to its high of
68 U.S. cents following the release of GDP figures by the
Australian Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Australian real gross domestic production on an average basis,
GDP(A), rose by a seasonally adjusted 1.5 percent in the September
quarter, making an increase of 3.6 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
The result was better than market expectations of an increase
in GDP of about 1.1 percent, which would have brought the annual
growth rate up to about 3.4 percent from 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank foreign exchange manager Peter Whitley said
there had been heavy selling of the major Southeast Asian
currencies again today.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the better-than-expected GDP numbers, Australia
continues to be caught up in the Asian debacle," Whitley said.
</P>
<P>
"The selling of the Australian dollar is a knee-jerk reaction
to what is happening in Southeast Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Against the Japanese yen, the Australian dollar finished steady
at 87.02/12.
</P>
<P>
It was also at 1.2012 German marks, from 1.2052 Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
