<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Prudent Opening of Financial Market Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Financial specialists and
policy makers said that opening of financial markets, though an
inevitable trend in the globe today, should be carried out in a
prudent manner.
</P>
<P>
In his closing remarks at the Second Conference on
International Financial Centers, an organizing official summed up
the discussions in the past two days by saying that financial
markets in developing or transitional economies should be opened
step by step in line with the economic development stage of those
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of capital market should be extremely prudent,"
warned Lu Hongjun, chairman of the International Financial Centers
Association. He pointed out that two fundamental elements led to
the recent financial crisis in Asia -- economic bubbles and
defects in financial system.
</P>
<P>
An open financial market and the free flow of capital are
desirable to create a vibrant financial center, but at the same
time, these centers should build up sound and efficient financial
system to stand the test of financial turbulence, said Lu.
</P>
<P>
He urged financial centers to establish sound and efficient
financial institution system, financial market mechanism, and
financial monitoring and supervisory framework.
</P>
<P>
A topical issue at the conference was on the Asian financial
jitters that first occurred in Thailand in July, then spilled over
to other parts of Southeast Asia, and in mid-October swept across
Northeast Asian countries like Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has thrown life ropes to
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea to help bail out their
battered economies with multi-billion-U.S. dollar rescue programs.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the conference were full of confidence in the
future economic growth in Asia, said a resolution passed today at
the seminar.
</P>
<P>
Financial specialists and policy markers from all over the
world presented dozens of papers at the meeting on capital flows
and financial integration in the globe, reforms of China's
financial system, Hong Kong's role as an international financial
center and others.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the conference was reform, transition and
consolidation of Asian financial centers to meet competition and
challenges in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the International Financial Center Association,
the World Bank and the IMF, the first such conference was held in
Shanghai, China, three and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
The organizers announced today that the third conference will
be held in New York, the United States, in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
