<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Unveils Medium-Term Budget Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has unveiled
budget projections for the next three years, which has given
priorities and contingencies and spending increases to education,
social services and the fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported today that the release of the policy by
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel Tuesday represented an important
step toward the openness of government budget policies and the
adoption of a three-year, rather a one-year budgeting cycle.
</P>
<P>
"For too long, budgets have been made behind closed doors,"
Manuel said.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy statement, government spending in the
next fiscal year would rise to a projected 202.1 billion Rand
(41.5 billion U.S. Dollars) from the 186.8 billion (38.5 billion
Dollars) in the present fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Revenue would rise 9.9 percent to 178.1 billion (36.7 billion
Dollars) from this year's 161.9 billion (33.4 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product (GDP) was forecast to grow three
percent in the next fiscal year, four percent in the following
and five percent in fiscal 2000-01. GDP growth this year is
estimated at less than two percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation was put at 7.5 percent in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government would be committed to containing the deficit
within four percent of the GDP this year and further reducing it
to 3.5 percent next year and to three percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The new feature of the policy would be the introduction of a
10-billion-Rand (2.1 billion Dollars) reserve fund, which would
make room for emerging new policy priorities and ensure funds
were available to deal with unexpected disasters.
</P>
<P>
The reserve would consist of two elements -- a policy reserve
and a contingency reserve. The contingency reserve would be two
billion Rand (410 million Dollars) in the next fiscal year and
the policy reserve three billion (620 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government would spend more on fighting crime, education,
welfare and health.
</P>
<P>
Spending on crime fighting would increase by about 9.5 percent
a year, from 18.3 billion (3.8 billion Dollars) this year to 24.1
billion (4.97 billion Dollars) in 2000. The annual growth in
spending on education would be 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The plan is expected to be tabled in parliament on March 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
