<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, IMF Finalize Talks on Terms of Bailout Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) today agreed finally on the terms of the IMF
bailout loan to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Deputy Prime Minister Lim Chang-yuel and visiting
International Monetary Fund (IMF) Managing Director Michel
Camdessus arrived at a complete agreement, South Korea's Yonhap
news agency reported. Camdessus flied into Seoul today.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the South Korean government, Lim signed a letter
of intent and handed it to Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement coming after a difficult 10-day
negotiations beginning November 24, the IMF and the United States
and Japan will give an assistance of about 57 billion U.S. dollars
for bailing out the South Korean economy from its current
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The first tranche of 10 billion U.S. dollars will arrive in the
country within the week.
</P>
<P>
South Korean officials said the the negotiations were difficult
and the terms are much harsher than expected.
</P>
<P>
Beside demands on the readjustment in South Korea's
macroeconomic target and restructuring measures in conglomerate
firms and financial sector, the IMF and the U.S., as well as
Japan, also asked South Korea to open its capital and monetary
market ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
"The government decided to accept most of the demands so as to
wrap up the IMF bailout talks as soon as possible," Yonhap quoted
a government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
South Korea accepted the IMF's demand to lower the GDP growth
rate, control rise of consumer price rate, reduce current-account
deficit, increase taxes, adoption of retrenchment monetary policy
and lowering debt rate and increasing managerial transparency in
conglomerate firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
