<HEADLINE> UNICEF Concerns Land-mines in Great Lakes Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) has expressed concerns over the increasing use of
land mines in the Great Lakes region, particularly in Burundi and
the border regions of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here today, Michel Sidibe, UNICEF
representative in Burundi, said that "from October 1996 to
October 1997, 49 incidents of land mines were reported in
Burundi," with some 40 people killed by land mines.
</P>
<P>
Since February this year, he said, there have been many more
reports of plantings and explosions mainly in the capital city of
Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
According to a UNICEF Uganda report, land mines have maimed
and killed hundreds of young children and adults since the
beginning of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, increasing numbers of women and
children have been killed and injured by mines in Kitgum district
in northern Uganda where the rebels have deliberately planted
mines to target the local civilians.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the West Nile areas of Moyo, Arua, Nebbi
and Ajumain bordering the Democratic Republic of Congo had also
been affected by land mines.
</P>
<P>
The Convention on the Prohibition of the Use, Stockpiling,
Production and Transfer of Anti-Personnel Mines and on their
Destruction, or the Ottawa Treaty, is being signed by various
countries beginning from today.
</P>
<P>
Shahida Azfar, Director of UNICEF's Eastern and Southern
Africa Regional Office, was quoted as describing the signing of
the treaty as a significant move toward eradicating land mines in
the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the land mines kill and maim some 26,000 men,
women and children each year all over the world with women and
children constituting 30 to 40 percent of all mine casualties.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF official predicted that some 27 African countries
would sign the Ottawa Treaty today and tomorrow in Ottawa,
Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
