<HEADLINE> PNG PM Blames Foreigners, Corrupt Elements for Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG) Prime
Minister Bill Skate tonight refused to resign from the leadership
and blamed the political crisis engulfing his government on
foreigners and corrupt elements.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech to the nation, Skate said his fight to
stop the cancer of corruption in PNG had triggered the setting-up
of bribery allegations against him, the Australian Associated
Press reported today in a dispatch from Port Moresby, the
country's capital.
</P>
<P>
Although refusing to name names, Skate said he had received
information from international sources that an Australia-based
organization might be behind a conspiracy to destabilize his
government.
</P>
<P>
He said he had made a request to the Australian High Commission
in Port Moresby to investigate the organization and he would pass
on to them any information he received, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
"Do not expect me to run away like a dog, I have done no
wrong," Skate said in a prepared address. "I will not let any
foreign interest destabilize my government."
</P>
<P>
In his first public statement since returning to the country at
the weekend, Skate defied the call from the Opposition for his
resignation, saying he would not resign and promising to pursue
other allegedly corrupt deals involving senior politicians.
</P>
<P>
The Skate government is now split with his former coalition
partners, Pangu and the Peoples Progress Party, defecting to the
Opposition.
</P>
<P>
Skate Sunday sacked the parties' respective leaders, former
deputy prime minister Chris Haiveta and former livestock minister
Andrew Baing.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister accused them of being behind a conspiracy to
discredit him after the Australian Broadcasting Corporation aired
videotapes last week showing him allegedly authorizing bribes
through Internal Affairs Minister Thomas Pelika.
</P>
<P>
Another of the tapes showed Skate bragging that he was the
godfather of Port Moresby's criminal gangs and ordering the
killing of a man. The prime minister said later he was drunk when
he made the remarks.
</P>
<P>
Both tapes were secretly filmed by a disaffected former PNG
government adviser, Australian businessman Mujo Sefa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
