<HEADLINE> Work of Sino-British Group Enters New Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The mission of the Sino-British
Joint Liaison Group (JLG) is coming to an end, allowing the JLG's
work to enter a new phase in the next two years, said Ambassador
Wang Guisheng, China's chief representative to the group.
</P>
<P>
Wang made his remarks today at a joint news conference by chief
JLG representatives from China and Britain. The conference was
held right after the two-day 41st session of the JLG, the group's
first meeting since Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the two chief representatives held a
joint press conference. The two shared the view that the joint
press conference itself implies the proper resolution of the Hong
Kong issue, and Sino-British relations have started a new chapter.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the future work of the JLG is to resolve the
remaining questions prior to Hong Kong's return and to further
implement the agreements between China and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The smooth transfer of power and steady transition were
accomplished in Hong Kong five months ago, he noted, and the
principles of "one country, two systems", Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong and a high degree of autonomy have been
carried out.
</P>
<P>
The existing capitalist system and way of life in Hong Kong
remain unchanged, which has won favorable comment from the
international community, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the resolution of the Hong Kong question should
first be attributed to Deng Xiaoping's great concept of "one
country, two systems" and at the same time to the concerted
efforts of the Chinese and British sides.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the two sides held discussions on
Vietnamese refugees and boat people staying in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the problem is caused by Britain which used to make
Hong Kong the primary harbor for Vietnamese refugees, and that
China regrets that the problem was not settled before July 1.
</P>
<P>
Alan Paul, chief representative for the British, said that his
country is content with the implementation of the "one country,
two systems" principle and the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The next JLG session will be held in London.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
