<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia's mining and
bluechip resource stocks were back in favor today, driving the
stock market higher in the face of weaker exchanges in Japan and
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 37.6 points or 1.5 percent
stronger at 2562.4.
</P>
<P>
The all mining sector added 3.8 percent or 21.6 points to 585.2
while the all resources jumped three percent or 33 points to
1127.0.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the resource stocks have been a bit oversold and
investors are starting to see some value there," Reynolds &AMP; Co's
Grant Williams said.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe it's the start of the pre-Christmas rally we are
supposed to have. But I expect resources will remain volatile," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the Nikkei 225 index dipped 324.78 points to a close
of 16585.51 as selling undermined sentiment in selected leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Australian share market's industrials index held firm,
climbing 45.8 points to a close of 4365.6.
</P>
<P>
Among the miners, WMC surged 30.9 cents, Comalco gained 27
cents, Pasminco moved up six cents, while MIM increased three
cents to 1.15 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
BHP led the resources index, up 47 cents to 14.61 Australian
dollars, Rio Tinto ended 40 cents better, Woodside improved 31
cents and Southern Pacific climbed 20 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index strengthened 24.7 points or 2.85 percent to 891,
while bullion was selling 40 U.S. cents softer at 293.00 U.S.
dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover topped 389.62 million, worth 1.09 billion
Australian dollars (741 million U.S. dollars). Rises outpaced
falls 656 to 458, with 407 steady.  
</P>
