<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Mark 90th Anniversary of Chinese Modern Drama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the birthplace of
Chinese drama, will have seven generations of drama performers on
stage to mark the 90th anniversary of the birth of modern drama in
China.
</P>
<P>
The drama artists have jointly performed a symphonic poem of
"Glorious Course" last night at the Shanghai Drama Institute,
reviewing episodes of excellent dramas of different historical
periods. The performance signified the beginning of a two-week
birthday celebration activities.
</P>
<P>
There will be a total of 12 dramas to be staged during the
period of December 2-15, including "Boyhood of Deng Xiaoping",
"Old Comedy", "Big Circus", and "Public Kitchen".
</P>
<P>
Chinese modern drama started with Wang Zhongsheng in 1907 when
his drama troupe Chun Yang (Spring Sun) put on stage "Uncle Tom's
Cabin" in Shanghai as the first Chinese drama.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, professional performers and amateurs from Shanghai,
Tianjin and Nanjing will hold discussions on the history and
future of Chinese drama.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Oil Revenue Higher Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The oil revenue for Nigeria, the
world's sixth largest oil producer, will be much higher than the
government had expected in the 1997 budget, The Vanguard
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government in the budget projected an oil revenue of 243
billion Naira (one dollar equals to 22 Naira, according to the
official exchange rate), with a base price of 17 dollar per
barrel and an OPEC export quota of 1.865 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, however, projected that Nigeria's revenue from
crude oil export may stand at well over 300 billion Naira (about
13.6 billion dollars according to official rate) by the end of
the year, due to favourable prices and higher-than-quota export.
</P>
<P>
In the last 12 months, OPEC's basket of seven premium crude,
including Nigeria's bonny light have been averaged at 20 dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Further more, the newspaper said, Nigeria's actual crude oil
export is much higher than the OPEC quota, except in March, when
the export averaged 1,710,293 barrels.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted figures from the Ministry of Petroleum
Resources as showing that in January, the country's export was
about 1.94 million barrels a day without condensate, which is
outside the OPEC quota, and 2.054 million barrels a day with
condensate.
</P>
<P>
In February, the crude oil export stood at 1.92 million
barrels a day without condensate. With condensate, it was 2.4
million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
The figure in March was the lowest, with an export of 1.71
million barrels a day without condensate, or 1.8 million barrels
a day with condensate.
</P>
<P>
The export came to the highest in April, when the daily export
hit 2.48 million barrels without condensate, otherwise it was
2.54 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
Between May and July, the daily export with condensate run
from 2.03 million barrels to 2.22 million barrels. It dipped a
little in August to 1.97 million barrels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
