<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 39,000 Postgraduates to Join Job Market in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- About 51,000 postgraduate
students will complete their education at Chinese universities
next year.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 12,000 will return to their work units, which
leaves 39,000 to find jobs, the State Education Commission (SEC)
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) stipulates that under
China's policies, most postgraduates can adopt a "two-way choice,"
that is to say, students can choose their jobs and employers can
choose the students.
</P>
<P>
China's demand for postgraduate students is expected to
increase in 1998. Supply falls short of demand in most of the
majors and supply exceeds demand only in a few majors, such as
history and archeology, according to an SEC official.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to the needs of Chinese colleges,
scientific research institutions and state-owned high-technology
enterprises, the SEC official said.
</P>
<P>
The SEC is dedicated to guiding postgraduates to where they are
most needed and is encouraging them to go to central and western
China, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The SEC will hold talent exchange fairs on Dec. 19 in Shanghai
and Dec. 24 in Beijing to help place the students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
