<HEADLINE> E. Africa Prepares for Cooperation Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda are
preparing an East African Treaty on cooperation which is expected
to be signed by the heads of state of the three countries by next
April, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
An on-going meeting among the three member states of the East
African Cooperation (EAC) will generate the treaty document this
week in the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha, where the EAC
headquarters is based, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The meeting's topics include the position of instruments for
EAC, desired position of instruments and the advantages of
upgrading the current EAC agreement to a treaty.
</P>
<P>
"The proposed treaty will be an instrument meant to facilitate
east Africa's integration and accelerated economic development,
strengthening of political cooperation and enhancing the region's
performance in the integrated global market," said EAC Deputy
Executive Secretary Fulgence Kazaura.
</P>
<P>
He said the treaty will define the EAC institutions and
members' relationship. It will also establish a decision-making
process and try to make the EAC a legal entity acting in the
common interests of the member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
