<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Warns Transition Saboteurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Sani Abacha vowed on Tuesday that the military government would
resist any attempt by any individual or group to derail the
transition to civil rule program toward a successful handover on
October 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
"Let me also assure you that this administration considers the
transition program and democracy as crucial to nigeria's
evolution as the true giant of Africa," Abacha said at a national
conference on national reconciliation and the political
transition program.
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by the National Reconciliation
Committee, was held in the capital Abuja four days ahead of the
election of the state houses of assembly due the forthcoming
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The coming election, to be monitored by some independent
foreign observers, is an important step of the transition
program.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, national assembly election will begin next
April, while both governors and president will be elected in the
July-August period, with the president put in place on October 1.
</P>
<P>
According to Abacha, the conference is important to the
transition program because "we strongly believe that
reconciliation as opposed to discord, hatred, violence and war,
is fundamental to the success of the political transition program
of this administration".
</P>
<P>
He also announced that his regime has succeeded in restoring
peace, law, order ans stability to the country although it cannot
claim "there is total absence of discord".
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that Abacha's appeal for national
reconciliation is part of his efforts to create a favorable
environment for next year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In a series of speeches he made recently, Abacha promised to
improve the national economy and create more jobs. He also
launched the country's first long-term socio-economic development
program code named vision 2010.
</P>
<P>
Under the blueprint, Nigeria will be transformed into a
developed country by the year 2010 with per capita income
reaching 1,600 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
All this, in addition to the support of the army and his
favorable position as head of state, is expected to help Abacha
defeat other presidential candidates if he wants to do so.
</P>
<P>
There are only several months to go before the election and
Abacha has not signaled his intention to run for presidency.
Neither have the five registered political parties produced their
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
Some of the parties have earlier said they either would invite
Abacha to be their presidential aspirant or have extended the
invitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
