<HEADLINE> Germany Sees Major Slowdown in Exports to Japan in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany's remarkable export boom
to Japan in recent years has come to a halt in 1997, the German
federal statistics office announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data released by the Wiesbaden-based
statistics office, German exports to Japan suffered a 1.2 percent
drop in the second quarter of this year after a modest increase of
2.3 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
These represented a major turnaround in a long-term trend after
Germany saw its exports to Japan jump by 13.6 percent in 1994, 5.2
percent in 1995 and 12.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The steady expansion of Germany's exports to Japan in recent
years have combined with a virtual stagnation in Japan's exports
to Germany in the same period, which has helped Germany to reduce
its traditional trade deficits with Japan from 16.2 billion marks
(9.2 billion U.S. dollars) in 1994 to 12.9 billion marks (7.3
billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japan now takes in some three percent of Germany's total
exports, making it the country's second-largest export market
outside Europe, just after the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
