<HEADLINE> Largest Outbreak of Suspected Monkeypox Reported in D.R. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 511 cases of
suspected monkeypox were identified between February 1996 and
October 1997 in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, former
Zaire, according to the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
This constitutes the "largest reported outbreak of suspected
monkeypox" ever, WHO pointed out in a press release issued here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the most recent investigation, 419 suspected cases were
identified in 78 villages in five health zones of Katako-Kombe and
Lodja. Serum has been collected from over 300 cases, while
crusted scabs and vesicular fluid have been collected from 19
cases with active disease.
</P>
<P>
Human monkeypox is a severe systemic disease clinically similar
to smallpox. It is a rare sporadic zoonosis caused by the
monkeypox virus, an orthopoxvirus enzootic among mammals,
including monkeys and squirrels, in the rain-forest of western and
central Africa.
</P>
<P>
Clinical disease in the outbreaks after February 1996 has been
milder than that reported in outbreaks during the 1980s, WHO said,
but the person-to-person transmission has been higher, as
confirmed in the WHO Weekly Epidemiological Report to be published
on December 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
