<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will meet South African President Nelson
Mandela and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki during her visit next
week, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Albright's visit to South Africa from December 12 to 14 is
part of her six-nation African tour, which is focused mainly on
the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Ministry spokesman Marco Boni said
Albright's visit would be partly contributed to preparations for
a state visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton in the first half of
1998.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the U.S. embassy in Pretoria said Tuesday that
Albright has requested meetings with Mandela, Mbeki and Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said he expected the meeting with Mandela to be
a courtesy visit, while her talks with Mbeki will entail "nuts
and bolts issues."
</P>
<P>
The two countries are at loggerheads concerning South Africa's
arms sales and relations with countries like Iran, Libya and
Cuba, which were labeled by Washington as "rogue states".
</P>
<P>
The United States accused these countries of sponsoring
terrorism and was trying to isolate them internationally.
</P>
<P>
In defiance of Washington's disapproval, Pretoria insisted on
developing good relations with these countries on the ground that
they had supported the struggle against apartheid led by the
African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
Mandela visited Libya twice in October and awarded Libyan
leader Omar Muammar Gaddafi with the Order of Good Hope, South
Africa's greatest honor for foreign citizens. 
</P>
