<HEADLINE> Symposium Explores Cooperation Between China, Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUANZHOU, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Experts and scholars attending
an international symposium held in this eastern China port city of
Fujian Province have expressed confidence in expanding economic
and trade relations between China and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The three-day "China and Southeast Asia" symposium, which
closed today, was jointly sponsored by United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organizations (UNESCO), UNESCO China
National Committee, Fujian Province and Quanzhou governments.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and overseas scholars said that -- because of
historical and geographic reasons -- economic and trade relations,
and maritime cooperation between China and Southeast Asian nations
long have existed and gradually developed into a trade network.
</P>
<P>
Scholars from the French College of Far East Studies said the
South China Sea region's role in the history of Southeast Asia is
as important as that of the Mediterranean is in the history of
western civilization.
</P>
<P>
Li Guoliang, a professor with the Institute of Southeast Asian
Studies of Xiamen University, said that as the economy of
Southeast Asian countries develops rapidly, coupled with an
expansion of a global economy, China has become one of investment
target countries for enterprise groups from Southeast Asian
countries to carry out transnational operations.
</P>
<P>
While calling for a combination of competition and mutual aid
in economic development and expanding maritime cooperation between
China and Southeast Asian nations, some Chinese experts predicted
an expansion in the long-existing friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the symposium also discussed the role of
overseas Chinese in advancing the economy of Southeast Asia and in
promoting economic and trade exchanges between China and Southeast
Asia, as well as the impact of the handover of Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
