<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Researchers Recover Nylon from Old Tires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 3 (Xinhua)-- Indian researchers at the
Shriram Institute for Industrial Research here have developed a
new technology to recover nylon from used tires, Press Trust of
India (PTI) said today.
</P>
<P>
Traditional technologies recycle rubber from worn-out tires
which is used by rubber reclaimer industries.
</P>
<P>
The waste left after rubber reclamation consists of cord waste
(magus) which comprises 15-20 percent of tire. This rubber in
which nylon is embedded is used to recover nylon. If left
untreated, it causes environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
Nylon content in magus varies between 45 and 60 percent
depending on the efficiency of rubber reclamation process.
Laboratory scale tests on recycling magus to obtain nylon have
given impressive results with good economic potential.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
