<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenyang Says Farewell to Steelyard Scales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang banned the use of
steelyard scales in public markets on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Administration Bureau in the
capital city of northeastern China's Liaoning Province banned
sales and the use of steelyard scales in urban areas in a bid to
protect the interests of customers. Venders found in violation of
the regulation will be subject to fines ranging between 500-2,000
yuan (60-240 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"I no longer have to worry about vendors manipulating
steelyard scales," said a happy middle-aged female shopper buying
groceries at the May 1st Store.
</P>
<P>
Inexpensive and portable steelyard scales have long be popular
with venders in Chinese markets. However, unscrupulous vendors
have discovered numerous methods to cheat customers by
manipulating the scales.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from Shenyang's Technological
Supervision Bureau, measurements on public scales must be clearly
visible to both buyers and sellers, and the requirement is common
international practice and the vast majority of countries have
banned the use of steelyard scales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
