<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Urged to End Nurses' Strike Before </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Medical
Practitioners and Dentists Union (KMPDU) has urged the government
to immediately enter into dialogue with nurses to end their pay
strike which has crippled most public hospitals in the country.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory technicians and clinical officers joined the strike
on Tuesday, the fifth day of the strike and two days after the
government issued an order asking all nurses to immediately
resume work or face the sack, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The unregistered KMPDU blamed the government for mishandling
and fueling the strike "by their empty rhetoric", saying the
nurses' grievances are genuine and the government should solve
the problem through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The impression being created by the government that doctors
and paramedics can deal with the situation was false and
misleading, said a statement issued by KMPDU on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The strike by nurses automatically means that doctors are
technically on strike," the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The nurses reiterated that they will go on with the
strike which started from Friday, until their demands for
minimum monthly pay of 30,000 Shillings (484 U.S. Dollars) and
better allowance are met.
</P>
<P>
The strike, reportedly backed by newly-registered opposition
party Safina and the Kenya Medical Association, simmered the
political atmosphere as it took place on the eve of the December
29 general elections.  
</P>
