<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Commemorates Late Hong Kong Patriot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese personnel in scientific
and educational circles held a meeting here today to mark the 90th
anniversary of the birth of the late Hong Kong patriot, Wong Kwan
Cheng.
</P>
<P>
This year is also the 10th anniversary of cooperation between
the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and the K.C. Wong Education
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Wong Kwan Cheng, a successful Hong Kong industrialist, had
concerned himself with educational and social welfare causes on
China's inland areas as well as in Hong Kong. He had donated to
more than 20 schools and institutes, including the China Welfare
Fund for the Handicapped, Soong Ching Ling Foundation and China
Cancer Research Foundation.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Wong contributed 100 million U.S. dollars to establish
the K.C. Wong Education Foundation to support inland scholars for
study and research abroad.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, CAS and the foundation began cooperating to provide
financial assistance to researchers from colleges, universities
and research institutes for attendance at international academic
conferences and for overseas research. The foundation also
encourages overseas Chinese scholars to work in the CAS.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yongxiang, president of the academy, said at today's meeting
that CAS will continue its cooperation with the K.C. Wong
Education Foundation to carry forward Wong's patriotic spirit and
to make unremitting efforts to train more scientists and
technicians for China.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the foundation donated one million
U.S. dollars to CAS to set up a post-doctoral fund, and another
one million Hong Kong dollars (130,000 U.S. dollars) to the Purple
Mountain Observatory in Nanjing to train scientists specializing
in research on the planets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
