<HEADLINE> News Analysis: CHT Peace Accord Can Be Implemented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited peace agreement
on the Chittagong Hill Tracks (CHT) tribal issues signed in
Bangladesh Tuesday is certain to be implemented because it is in
the interest of the whole country, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The historic document put an end to a bloody, guerrilla warfare
that lasted for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been praised by both the ruling party leaders
and supporters and the CHT tribal leaders and tribal people. They
share the view that the accord would help achieve all-round
development of the CHT, and Banglee and tribal people will live in
peace together and make contribution to the national economic
development.
</P>
<P>
But they also cautioned that hard and persistent efforts must
be made to implement the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The whole country must sharpen their vigilance against all
kinds of conspiracy aimed at sabotaging the implementation of the
accord, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said right after the
agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
Jyotirindra Bodhipriya Larma, chief of the Parbatya Chattagram
Jana Sanghati Samity (PCJSS) and also a signatory to the accord,
said, "It is a difficult task to sign a treaty and a much more
difficult job to implement it."
</P>
<P>
The ruling party, Awami (people's) League, will surely face
those who will try to create disturbances in opposing the accord,
some observers said.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) held a
Standing Committee meeting Tuesday night, strongly criticizing the
present government for signing the accord and calling it as
"anti-national, unequal and anti-constitution agreement".
</P>
<P>
After reviewing the current political situation, the meeting
called for greater unity of all the nationalist patriotic forces
"to save the sovereignty and independence of the country". The
meeting also decided to form a review committee to examine the
legal aspects of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the BNP will likely announce tougher action programs
against the government.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, temporary camps of the army and other
security forces in the CHT will be closed, with only three
cantonments and three border-force garrisons remaining. This might
cause some problems such as social order and security and more
commodity smuggling along the border with India.
</P>
<P>
The government, in accordance with the agreement, will provide
50,000 taka (about 1,100 U.S. dollars) to each member of the PCJSS
who will return from India and exempt the members from outstanding
bank loans. This means that a large amount of money will be needed
for tens of thousands of tribal people. It is a heavy task for the
government to accomplish, some analysts commented.
</P>
<P>
Though there are some difficulties ahead for implementing the
agreement, the present government will surely try by every
possible means to cherish the hard-won achievements in resolving
the CHT issue.
</P>
<P>
Some changes might take place in the political situation in
this South Asian country because the opposition party and its
supporters will take tougher action programs against the
government.
</P>
<P>
However, the peace accord will be surely implemented because it
is in the interest of the country, observers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
