<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 140 Woman Die in Childbirth Daily in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 140 women die everyday or
one dies every 10 minutes during childbirth in Nigeria, bringing
the total number of such deaths to over 50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
This large number of prenatal deaths is symptomatic of the
parlous state of Nigeria's health care system, according to a
medical expert.
</P>
<P>
Also symptomatic of the declining state of the health care
system is the fact that Nigeria has one of the highest child
mortality rates in the world, said Professor Adetokunbo O. Lucas,
a consultant to the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's child mortality rate is at 19 deaths in 1,000
births, higher than Cameroun, Ghana, Kenya, not to mention
developed countries like Britain and the United States, he said
during a lecture on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Describing Nigeria's health care sector as being in crisis,
Lucas said, "Nigeria's hospitals are veritable death traps;
instead of relieving pain, they intensify it; there is shortage
of drugs; equipment has broken down, no water supply; we are, as
a nation, not as healthy as we should be."
</P>
<P>
Lucas, seen by Nigerians as world-renowned medical
practitioner and scholar, attributed the poor state of the health
care system of the country to inadequate revenue allocation, and
the decline in infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
To remedy the situation, he called for a re-alignment and
cooperation among the five key players in the health care sector
-- the people, the public sector, the private sector,
professionals and other partners, in addition to reasonable and
sizeable increase in the health budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
