<HEADLINE> Bhopal Gas Tragedy Anniversary Observed in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 3 (Xinhua)-- Prayer meetings and protests
were held in Bhopal city, capital of Madhya Pradesh in the middle
of India, today to mark the 13th anniversary of the Bhopal gas
disaster that left hundreds of people dead and thousands impaired
for life in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that voluntary organizations staged
protests outside the Union Carbide Plant and burnt effigies of
Warren Anderson, who was chairman of the Union Carbide Corporation
(UCC) when the disaster took place.
</P>
<P>
The worst-ever tragedy occurred in Bhopal city in the wake of
the leakage of lethal methyl isocyanate gas from the U.S.-owned
Union Carbide Plant on the night of December 2, 1984.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of workers in the plant and residents in the city died
due to the poisoning. Life for the seriously injured has become an
unending battle for survival as many families in the city lost
earning members in the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Even children born much after the disaster have shown some
abnormalities as a result of their parents' exposure to the methyl
isocyanate gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
