<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Parliament Calls for Spending Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese National Assembly
(NA) has urged the government to cut spending in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the Vietnam Investment Review, Vietnam's
over-spending this year is expected to be equivalent to 4.8
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
However, the the government must keep its over-spending within
3.5-4 percent of the GDP, Vice Chairman of the NA's Economic and
State Budget Committee Ngo Dinh Giao said.
</P>
<P>
The report said Vietnam's total revenue in 1998 is expected to
increase by only four percent but its total spending is set to
rise eight percent.
</P>
<P>
The NA deputies said that the government should spend more on
investment rather than on extravagant items.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the government use foreign investment more
effectively.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Nguyen Sing Hung told the NA that state
administrative expenses will be slashed by 15 percent compared
with 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
