<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Chinese Vice Premier Praises China-NZ Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Chinese Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Huang Hua said here today that the Chinese
government has all along attached importance to its relations with
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Huang made the remarks at a ministerial lunch held in his honor
and to mark the 25th anniversary of the establishment of
diplomatic relations between China and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, Huang Hua signed on behalf of the
Chinese government the communique on the establishment of
diplomatic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we are gratified to see frequent exchange of visits
between leaders of the two countries and steady growth of our
economic relations and trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, he mentioned the visit to New Zealand in June
this year by Chinese Vice Premier Zhu Rongji and the upcoming
visit by Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
Huang Hua also recalled the attendance by NZ Deputy Prime
Minister Winston Peters of the functions on Hong Kong's return to
China in July and his friendly remarks about the event. In
September, Peters visited China and Prime Minister Jim Bolger has
just concluded a visit to China.
</P>
<P>
Huang pointed out that an outstanding feature of the China-New
Zealand relations is the rapid growth of economic relations as
well as marked increase of trade.
</P>
<P>
For the past six years or so, two-way trade has been growing at
an annual average of 23.8 percent and the total trade volume hit a
record high of 634 million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Located in the Asia-Pacific, both China and New Zealand are
members of the APEC and ASEAN Regional Forum, thus sharing
extensive common ground in promoting regional trade and economic
cooperation and safeguarding regional security," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
"Relations of long-term stability and mutually beneficial
cooperation between the two countries not only serve the common
interests of the two peoples, but also facilitate the maintenance
of peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region and the world at
large," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Among those attending the lunch were NZ Deputy Prime Minister
Winston Peters and Foreign Minister Don Mckinnon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
