<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Idea of Security Zones Discussed at Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The newly formed Israeli
government committee planning for a troop redeployment in the West
Bank met for the first time here today and discussed an idea of
setting up security zones.
</P>
<P>
The committee, formed November 30 by the cabinet and also
called mini-cabinet, is headed by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, with Foreign Minister David Levy, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai and Intrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon as
its three other members.
</P>
<P>
Sharon attended today's meeting with his own map delineating
two "essential security zones," one parallel to the Jordan River
and the other east of the 1949 armistice line.
</P>
<P>
The Jordan Valley zone, according to Sharon's map, would be 20
kilometers wide and the strip east of the armistice line
overlooking the coastal plain 7 to 10 kilometers wide.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said Tuesday night that these zones are necessary to
enable the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) to cope with the
inevitable establishment of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The narrower zone along the western hill slopes of the
West Bank would protect Israel's most densely populated region,
while the wider zone spanning the Jordan River Valley would
separate the Palestinian state from Jordan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said he is prepared to spell out in detail his
geographical, strategical and political concepts to the other 3
members of the cabinet team charged with demarcating the depth
and location of the second-stage troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Those sectors of the proposed security zones which are
populated by Palestinians would be tantamount to "islands" within
an Israeli-controlled sea, he said, adding that the IDF would
maintain total control of security within them, but the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) would provide their non-Israeli
residents with schooling, health services and other civilian
needs.
</P>
<P>
The underlying idea, in Sharon's opinion, is for Israel to cede
as little territory as possible in this second troop redeployment
process while being prepared to give up that much more in the next
phase.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Palestinian statehood, Sharon said he is sided
with the government's opposition to the Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
But as a realist, he said, it is impossible to ignore the facts
on the ground or bury one's head in the sand.
</P>
<P>
"The Oslo Accords mean Palestinian statehood...that the
Palestinian Authority has diplomatic missions in 100
countries...and its passports are accepted worldwide, including the
United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for today's meeting, Mordechai gathered top
defense officials and IDF brass in his Tel Aviv office
Tuesday to mull various options for the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
His plan for a troop pullback from the West bank calls
for establishing "three blocs of Palestinian-controlled regions"
focusing on Jenin and Nablus in the north and Hebron in
the south and some Jewish settlements surrounded by Palestinian
rule.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the peace movement group "Peace Now" called for
the evacuation of 25 Jewish settlements from the West Bank
and Gaza Strip and for 50 percent of the West Bank to be
handed over to the Palestinians as part of the interim
agreement before final-status talks begin.
</P>
<P>
The plan on redeployment formulated by the committee will be
handed over to the cabinet for approval, and it would take
some time for the committee to draw up the redeployment plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
