</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Judged in Bordeaux for crimes against humanity, former Vichy
official Maurice Papon affirmed that he had saved 130 Jews from
deportation to Nazi death camps. An inquiry by Liberation proved
that this is a lie. Through tracing the history of the 130 people,
it appears that Papon had never taken any initiative in writting
off their names from the list of deportation. Moreover, 120 of them
were not Jews.
</P>
<P>
-- The London conference on Nazi Gold opened Tuesday, wavering
between the role of a judge and a historian. More than 240 experts
from 40 countries responded to the British invitation to shed light
on the gold robbed by the Nazis, washed by neutral states, and
recovered by the Allies without doing justice to the victims of the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Le Figaro, the Minister of National
Education, Research and Technology Claude Allegre said that the
Socialist Party is entering a period of ideological transition which
will neither lead it toward a Communist Party nor toward a
conversion of Blairism (in reference to the New Labor movement of
Tony Blair). ``Lionel Jospin tries to invent a new way which passes
neither by liberalism nor by the old moons of Socialism,'' he said,
adding ``modern Socialism'' stresses ``good government'' rather than
``big government.''
</P>
<P>
-- The French judicial authorities began to investigate the
multi-billion financial loss of the public insurance group GAN as
early as the spring this year. The Minister of Justice Elisabeth
Guigou said at the National Assembly on Tuesday that ``the fight
against financial crimes is a priority for the government.''
</P>
