<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches European Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian booster rocket
Proton-K successfully blasted off with a European communication
satellite Astra-1G from the Baikonur space centre earlier this
morning, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth commercial launch of rocket Proton.
</P>
<P>
The Astra satellite is devised to relay television and radio
programs to western Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia charges average 70 million U.S. dollars for one Proton
take-off. The cost of this launch is not known yet.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the Russian Strategic Missile Forces said that
the satellite, schemed to work in orbit for 15 years, will go off
the Proton booster at 8.30 a.m. Moscow time.
</P>
<P>
Russia is expected to launch five Astra satellites in
accordance with the contract between Moscow's Khrunishev Space
Research and Development Center, the manufacturer of Protons, and
the European company SES, the satellite's owner.
</P>
<P>
The first Astra satellite was placed in orbit in April 1996,
while another two are scheduled for 1998 and the last one for
1999, the Itar-Tass said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
