<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU's CO2 Emissions Up 1.7 Percent in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- European Union-wide emissions
of carbon dioxide from fuel combustion in 1995 were 1.7 percent up
from the 1994 level, European Report said today.
</P>
<P>
The journal quoted EU's statistical agency, Eurostat, as saying
that EU member states disgorged a total of 3,048 million tons of
carbon dioxide in 1995 despite efforts to curb CO2 emissions.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the EU countries spewed 2,997 million tons of carbon
dioxide into the atmosphere, compared with 3,088 million tons
recorded in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau said seven of the 15 EU
member states saw a fall in 1995, but it was not enough to offset
rises totalling 69.2 million tons in the other eight member states.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the seven member states totalled 18.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The trend in Germany, the EU's largest producer of CO2
emissions, is still down, despite a 1.7-percent rise in industrial
production in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg posted the biggest fall in 1995 with an 18.7 percent
decrease due to the closure of blast furnaces in the country's
iron and steel industry.
</P>
<P>
The largest rise from 1994 to 1995 was Portugal's 7.9 percent,
although its emissions still formed some 1.6 percent of the EU
total.
</P>
<P>
In the European Union, the largest emissions rise was the 2.9
percent resulting from electricity generation. Thermal power
stations are responsible for over 30 percent of the total
emissions.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 rise of CO2 emissions was due to ever-increasing
demand for electricity, up 12.9 percent over 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
