<HEADLINE> SADC in Need of 27 Million Tons of Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Kaire Mbuende, Executive
Secretary of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
announced here today that the regional grouping is in need of 27
million tons of grain to eliminate the after-math brought by the
El Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambique News Agency quoted the visiting secretary as
saying that a part of the grain could be imported from outside
the SADC, while some be purchased from countries such as Zimbabwe
and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the grain, he said, port construction in
Mozambique and South Africa should be enhanced to be facilitated
for grain transport.
</P>
<P>
He cited Beira Port and Maputo Port in Mozambique and Port
Elizabeth in South Africa as good ones for loading and oo-loading
the aided grain.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende also revealed that SADC member states have been
holding regular consultations to make common strategies for
eliminating the losses caused by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
"The southern African region is studying on more appropriate
measures to reduce drought damages," he said, adding that a
meeting was held last month in Botswana to discuss an
anti-drought plan for SADC countries. 
</P>
