<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructured Coal Enterprise on Track With Market Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The market, for the first time in history, emerged at the
barometer high-level decision-makers used to control and adjust
production. Mines under the administration, formerly nothing more
than inert coal producers, were granted more rights and allowed to
play a more active role in marketing and sales.
</P>
<P>
The reform added great impetus to the enthusiasm of producers.
The Qianjiaying Mine, for example, sustained successive years of
heavy losses after entering operations in 1988. Operators
responded to the system transformation by dispatching teams to
"seek new markets", with said teams attempting to attract
customers rather than simply waiting for them to place purchase
orders.
</P>
<P>
The Majiagou Mine underwent a surprising transformation
following the reform. The mine, which recorded losses of 24
million yuan in 1996, reversed its loss-making situation and
earned profits of 2.27 million yuan for the first ten months this
year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the work force in Kailuan exhibited greater
efficiency. By the end of October this year, it had transferred
some 8,282 employees to new positions, and had terminated the
employment of 5,808 temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
Four years of arduous efforts have yielded notable returns. The
administration earned profits in 1994, with only three of
Kailuan's ten mines operating in the red, compared with the eight
loss-making operations in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The administration's taxes and profits have continued to rise
in ensuing years, with profits for the January-October period this
year soaring to 62 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
One noted Chinese economist referred to an investigation of
Kailuan by noting that the ultimate reason for state enterprises
operating in the red can be summarized as the "market
inflexibility syndrome." According to the economist, "Changing all
of the habitual operational methods in place under the planned
economy has been a painful process. Nonetheless, those who have
completed restructuring ahead of their counterparts will survive
and will win out in the market economy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructured Coal Enterprise on Track With Market Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kailuan Coal Mining
Administration, formerly the major loss-making enterprise in
China's coal industry, is once again earning profits following
management restructuring geared to the market economy.
</P>
<P>
Kailuan, which was established 119 years ago, is China's
largest coking coal producer. The administration operated under
the rigid planned economic system which for decades required
enterprises to engage in the "planned" formulation of everything
from production targets to building kindergartens.
</P>
<P>
The administration found itself unable to remain in step with
the changing situation accompanying the transition to a market
economy. Kailuan began operating in the red in 1986, with losses
soaring to 297 million yuan by 1990, the largest loss volume for
any enterprise in the nation's coal mining sector.
</P>
<P>
Just as many other state enterprises, Kailuan suffered what has
been called the "big enterprise syndrome" -- industrial giants
with an excessively large redundant work force. Kailuan hit a peak
employment level of 130,000 people, with some 50 percent of
employees working for subsidiary units or logistic departments.
</P>
<P>
The addition of some 50,000 retirees and over 30,000 temporary
workers to the active work force meant that the livelihood of
close to 200,000 people depended on a single nonrenewable resource
-- coal.
</P>
<P>
Kailuan's management team decided to tackle the complicated
problem and stop the downward slide by comprehensively
restructuring the administration's management system. The target
centered on letting all workers help shoulder the burden and face
the mounting pressure from the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Offers Loan to Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank's International
Development Association (IDA) is to offer a loan of 199 million
U.S. dollars to help restore and upgrade electricity distribution
in Vietnam, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached two weeks ago during negotiations
between IDA representatives and several Vietnamese agencies.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the IDA will loan 189 million
dollars to upgrade Vietnam's 500 kilovolt national power grid in
central highlands and power lines in southern Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 10 million dollars of the loan is to help repair
damage caused last month by storm Linda.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-loan has a 10-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The loan is the biggest yet made by the IDA to Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
