<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ports to Use Electronic Data Interchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 3 (Xinhua) -- All major ports in ASEAN
countries will be using the Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) in
their daily operations by the year 1999, Malaysian Deputy
Transport Minister Wira Mohd Ali Rustam said today.
</P>
<P>
The EDI, where data on goods handled can be communicated
between ports through computer, would speed up ship movements and
the handling of cargoes in the region, he told reporters after
opening the 23rd ASEAN Port Association (APA) meeting in Petaling
Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
He said at present only the Port of Singapore Authority (PSA)
and Malaysia's Klang Port Authority were using the EDI in their
operations.
</P>
<P>
By using the EDI, the Singapore Port could clear goods within
24 hours while Port Klang does so in 48 hours, he said, adding
"But we will improve the EDI system at Port Klang eventually to
make it as efficient as the Singapore Port."
</P>
<P>
By the middle of next year, Malaysia's Penang and Pasir Gudang
ports would also be covered by the EDI, according to the deputy
minister.
</P>
<P>
Besides Singapore and Malaysia, ASEAN (Association of Southeast
Asian Nations) also comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 846 Enterprises Get Privatized in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Since the enterprises
privatization program was put into action in 1987, of the
1254 enterprises which were registered for privatization, 846
have been actualy privatized in the country, according to the
figures from the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry disclosed the figures at a workshop held
in the central Mozambican city of Beira on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the privatized companies, 90 percent were sold to
Mozambicans, the rest was sold to South Africans and Portugal,
the local newspaper " Noticias" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that after the enterprises privatization, the
national treasury had receiced more taxes from the enterprises, and
in these companies, business is generally turning for better and
their production and sales are on increase.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government has set the target to get all its
state-owned enterprises privatized within this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
