<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chip Firms Face Cost, Technological Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Semiconductor
Industry Association urged its members today to work together to
meet cost and technological challenges in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
When chip firms move to produce more complicated chips, the
cost and complexity of developing new technologies escalate, the
association said in a 196-page report.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the current cost for building a new plant to
develop semiconductors ranges from one to two billion
U.S. dollars, but will double in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the pace of introducing new generation of technology
has accelerated, said the report, pointing to the fact that there
are now four or five possible ways to make chips with ultra-small
features, but none of them is economical.
</P>
<P>
Since massive investments on research and development are
needed, the report urged chip makers to join hands to tackle the
increasing costs as the industry approaches the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The report also predicted other future challenges, including
getting to an even more condensed circuitry size on a silicon
wafer, moving from aluminum to copper interconnects to speed up
the electrical flow, and developing new packaging and designing
technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
