<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Official Stresses Need to Maintain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zimbabwean officer has
called on the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
countries to maintain the existing peace through strong military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This could be achieved by continuing with peace-keeping
missions whenever the need arose, said Trust Maphosa, Deputy
Secretary for Defense who is responsible for policy and
procurement on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Maphosa was addressing a technical meeting to develop
peace-keeping exercises in the region and enhance military
cooperation and confidence building measures in the sub-region.
At least 11 SADC member countries were represented at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, an initiative of the South African National
Defense Forces, was held in Harare because Zimbabwe successfully
organized Exercise Blue Hungwe in Nyanga of eastern Zimbabwe
early this year.
</P>
<P>
The idea to rotate the exercise followed Zimbabwean President
Mugabe's call to make it an annual exercise rotated among nations
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Maphosa said that it is important to note that as officers
from the region, they are faced with the task of examining the
strengths and weaknesses of the past peace-keeping exercises and
assisting each other in the preparation and planning of Exercise
Blue Crane.
</P>
<P>
Army brigadier Andre Bestbier, head of the South African
delegation, said the exercise will benefit all SADC countries'
armed forces as the idea of regional peace-keeping is fast
gaining support around the world.
</P>
<P>
It is vital that if anything props up in the SADC region, the
leaders have suitable peace-keepers ready for deployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
