<HEADLINE> Greenspan Predicts Stronger World Economy After Asia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan today predicted the global economy would
come to be stronger after some Asian countries overcome their
financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting with economists at the
Economic Club at New York tonight.
</P>
<P>
However Greenspan noted that a large number of Asian nations
should reshape their banking systems and open up their markets to
resume the rapid growth rates in the last years.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the ongoing Asian financial crisis, Greenspan
said that a "temporary slowdown or pause" in that region was
perhaps inevitable.
</P>
<P>
"While the adjustments may be difficult for a time, these
crises will pass," he said, stressing that "stronger individual
economies and a more robust and efficient international economic
and financial system will surely emerge in their wake."
</P>
<P>
"In most developed nations, banking systems appear reasonably
solid. Japan has been somewhat of an exception, but there have
been some positive signs there as well," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the Asian financial crisis is likely to help remove
governmental colors in the investment system of many Asian
countries, where finance played a key role in carrying out the
state's objectives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
