<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hewlett-Packard Leads Global Consortium on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Hewlett-Packard Co., one of
the U.S. biggest computer makers, is launching a global consortium
with major financial companies to establish electronic banking and
commerce on internet, the company reported today.
</P>
<P>
The move, which was called the First Global Commerce
initiative, will open electronic commerce's doors for more
traditional merchants and counter an aggressive drive into the
electronic commerce arena by International Business Machines
Corp., which has launched an advertising campaign aimed at
attracting businesses into its camp, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The consortium includes Electronic Data Systems Corp. of
Dallas, Hewlett-Packard and its Verifone commerce unit, the Royal
Bank of Canada, Sumitomo Credit of Japan and the banking of major
card vendors such as Visa International and Mondex, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey company, business over the Internet will
soar to more than 220 billion U.S. dollars by the year 2001, over
20 times more than its forecast for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
