<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Push Deeper Reforms in Rural Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Collectively owned enterprises in
rural China should change their existing unitary form of
organization to gain vitality, Vice Agricultural Minister Wan
Baorui said here today.
</P>
<P>
The reform would be carried out in various forms under criteria
favorable to promoting production growth, increasing the overall
strength of the socialist state and raising the people's living
standards, Wan said at the national conference on rural industrial
development which opened today in Hefei, capital of Anhui province.
</P>
<P>
All organizational forms such as share-stock partnership, stock
cooperatives, enterprise groups, leasing and mergers should be
utilized boldly, he said, but efforts will be taken to prevent
rushing headlong into mass action or practicing a single form.
</P>
<P>
Wan said that the limited stock company is a suitable ownership
form for large- and-medium-size enterprises or enterprise groups,
while the stock cooperative is a good form for medium- and
small-size firms as it combines the advantages of public and
private ownership.
</P>
<P>
He described mixed ownership as an effective form because it
can build a polarized investment pattern and make the rural
industrial enterprises optimize resources and production elements
to keep abreast of the market economy and socialized production.
</P>
<P>
The structural reforms will proceed in an orderly way and will
be completed in the next few years, Wan said.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister also outlined principles of capital
circulation, upgrading of the product mix, cooperation between
eastern and western China and small town construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
