<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Farmers Benefit from Mobile Classroom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 3 (Xinhua) -- In some remote towns and
villages in northeastern China's Liaoning Province, farmers could
be seen going in or out of a large van parked beside vegetable
fields.
</P>
<P>
Called a mobile classroom, the specially equipped van run by
Liaoning TV University has won favor with local farmers for its
video recorders, TV sets and a library of more than 700 videotapes.
</P>
<P>
The tapes are not for entertainment, but for learning
vegetable-raising techniques.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yancai, deputy head of Liaoning TV University, said that
his university uses the van in remote villages and towns to help
farmers learn through watching videotapes.
</P>
<P>
He said staff members in the van also answer questions from
farmers.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jie, a farmer at Sankuaishi Village, was worried about his
tomato crop, which was suffering from a disease. When the van
arrived near his fields, he learned how to overcome the disease.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that my tomato output will increase by 10 percent,"
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The van started its rounds in May. It contains 2,000 video
materials about farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
So far the van has gone to four cities and 20 towns and
villages where more than 4,000 farmers have used its resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
