<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Farmers Benefit from WFP Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A World Food Program (WFP)
project, coded WFPCHA3779, has considerably improved the living and
production conditions for farmers in six counties of central
China's Hunan and Hubei provinces.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qingquan, a farmer in Huayuan County in Hunan's Xiangxi
Tujia and Miao Nationalities Autonomous Prefecture, is one of the
successful examples, according to local government sources.
</P>
<P>
Liu turned less than a hectare of arid farmland into irrigated
field in 1991, and began to reap nearly 5,000 kilograms of grain
annually. Now his family no longer worries about food, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The program provided 7,779 tons of wheat free of charge to the
prefecture during the last five years, while the province
allocated 50 million yuan to support the effort.
</P>
<P>
The project area now has six reservoirs, four pumping stations
and 3,069 kilometers of irrigation canals. The forest coverage in
the area has raised from 25.8 percent to 33.4 percent at present
and more than 9,000 hectares of farmland have been improved.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 32,000 farmers have received technical training and
nearly 90 percent of the households in the area have learned how
to use practical and new techniques.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Relief Pattern in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The pattern of the Poverty
Relief Program in southwest China, a project funded with World
Bank loans, has proved effective and is spreading to more areas
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The new pattern centers on the injection of funds into a number
of sectors in recipient areas, including agriculture, rural
industry, infrastructure, education, health care, and labor
exportation sectors. The new pattern replaces the former practice
of allocating funds to a single sector.
</P>
<P>
Rural Chinese citizens have exhibited "great enthusiasm" for
the pattern, especially for measures introduced to improve
education, health care facilities and access to potable drinking
water, according to a World Bank representative, who also expressed
gratitude for efforts the Chinese government has made to introduce
the new pattern of poverty relief nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank launched the Poverty Relief Program in southwest
China in July, 1995, and plans to provide a total of 200 million
US dollars in low-interest loans for a 20-year term for Yunnan and
Guizhou provinces, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey revealed that most popular projects with rural
residents included projects to upgrade infrastructure, as well as
projects to improve education and health care. However,
respondents indicated that labor export and agricultural projects
offered the greatest benefits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
