<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997 to Be Hottest Year for Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- This year, 1997, is going to
set a record for Singapore as it will turn out to be the hottest
year ever since 1929 when climate records started being kept here,
the Straits Times said today.
</P>
<P>
Citing the nation's Meteorological Service, it said that with
less than a month to go to the end of the year, this year's annual
mean temperature is likely to hit 28.2 degrees Celsius, compared
to the fact that the mean temperature was 26.8 degrees Celsius in
the previous 36 years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, this year will be the first year that Singapore's
mean temperature exceeds 28 degrees Celsius, a rise of three
degrees from about 30 years ago when the average temperature was
25.2 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Service said that a lack of rain and clouds
induced by El Nino is driving temperatures up here. The El Nino
phenomenon is caused by the warming water in southern Pacific
waters. It occurs with varying strength every two to seven years,
lasts up to 18 months and affects weather patterns all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
The last time the El Nino hit Singapore was in 1994. This year,
it was said to be partly responsible for the bush fire in
Indonesia, which caused heavy haze that affected the entire
region.
</P>
<P>
A Meteorological Service spokesman was quoted as saying that
the dry weather conditions are expected to last into the first
half of the next year as El Nino will peak around April before
tapering off. A return to near normal weather conditions is
expected only in the second half of 1998, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0198 </DOCNO>
