<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five More Kenyans Killed in Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Five more people have been
killed by floods since Tana River in eastern Kenya burst its
banks three days ago, bringing the death toll to at least 15, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Four of them were said to be pastoralists who were swept away
by the floods when they attempted to save a camel from drowning.
</P>
<P>
Another victim, identified as Mohammed Alio Ibrahim, drowned
at Modagashe, Garissa District, the report quoted a senior
provincial administration official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 6,000 people in Tana River district had
to be evacuated for fear that they might be swept away by the
floods, District Commissioner John Litunda said Tuesday when
urging aid agencies to assist the government in providing food,
medicine and shelter for the evacuees.
</P>
<P>
North Eastern Provincial Commissioner Maurice Makhanu was also
forced to be evacuated from his residence in Garissa Town on
Tuesday to escape the surging floods.
</P>
<P>
The Tana River, the longest river in Kenya, swelled suddenly
on Monday night and engulfed a police station, law courts,
governmental buildings and untold residents' houses. Currently
half of the Garissa town is submerged.
</P>
<P>
The town now is threatened with more disasters if the river
continues to swell at the current speed and residents there have
been asked to move to areas outside a seven-kilometer strip along
the river.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been compounded by continuous torrential
rains and the opening of flood-gates of the four dams of the
Kindaru power project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
