<HEADLINE> Pakistan Acting Chief Justice Takes Oath </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Justice Ajmal Mian, the
senior most judge of Pakistan's Supreme Court took oath as the
acting Chief Justice here today.
</P>
<P>
Justice Said-uz-zaman Siddiqui administered the oath of office
to Ajmal at a ceremony held at the auditorium of the Supreme Court
building.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah, who has been restrained from
performing his duty as the chief justice, was not among the 15
apex court justices who were present at Ajmal's oath-taking
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a ten-member Supreme Court bench headed by Justice
Siddiqui unanimously suspended the appointment of Sajjad as the
chief justice on the ground that Sajjad was not the senior most
judge in the Court, as required in the country's constitution,
when he was appointed as Chief Justice in June 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Bench also asked the Federal Government and President
Farooq Leghari to immediately appoint Justice Ajmal as acting
Chief Justice.
</P>
<P>
President Farooq Leghari announced his resignation Tuesday
evening after refusing to de-notify Chief Justice Sajjad as
required by the government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sajjad has applied for a two-and-a-half-month leave, ending on
February 16,1998, when he attains the retirement age of 65.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
