<HEADLINE> Foreman's Promoters Urge Investigation of Judges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- George Foreman's promoters
sent a letter to the governor and attorney general of New Jersey
on Tuesday to protest Foreman's controvercial loss to Shannon
Briggs on November 22 at Atlanta City, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
The majority decision in favour of the 25-year-old Briggs met
with thunderous jeers from outside the ring when it was announced.
</P>
<P>
Judge Calvin Claxton had it 116-112 in favor of Briggs, and
judge Lawrence Layton scored it 117-113 for Briggs with Judge
Steve Weisfield drawing it 114-114.
</P>
<P>
Irving Azoff and Jeff Wald, Foreman's promoters, called for
Governor Christine Todd Whitman and Attorney General Peter
Verniero along with the Casino Control Commission and State
Athletic Control Board to investigate the judges of Foreman-Briggs
fight.
</P>
<P>
Larry Hazzard, who appointed the judges for the match, would
not accept a formal protest or appeal of the decision, according
to Wald.
</P>
<P>
Foreman said after the match that he didn't blame Briggs in any
way for the decision and wished him well instead.
</P>
<P>
Foreman, 48, announced he would hang up his gloves after the
loss, ending a pro career that began in 1969. 
</P>
