<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Stresses Basics in Math Teaching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 2 (Xinhua) -- How to teach math: Is it
right to make math more fun and interesting while downplaying
calculating exact answers? How much emphasis to put on the
fundamentals -- skills such as memorizing multiplication tables or
mastering formulas for finding the volume of a cone?
</P>
<P>
A bitter battle between advocates of more traditional
drill-and-practice approach, and supporters of a new program
emphasizing world problems and team solutions in California has
resulted in a first-round upshot this Monday.
</P>
<P>
The California Board of Education has endorsed a new math
standards for kindergarten through seventh grade to emphasize
correct answers and practices while discouraging the use of
calculators.
</P>
<P>
The new standards call for California's public school students
to memorize multiplication tables in third grade and master the
age-old routines of borrowing and carrying while adding and
subtracting. Long division, a skill that some educators believe is
obsolete in an age of calculators, would once again become a
staple starting in the fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
Although California's 1,000 school districts with 5.5 million
school children are not required to abide by the first statewide
math standards, they will be highly influential because they will
help shape new textbooks and the statewide standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
The new standards indeed present a sharp shift from the math
methods that began taking hold in California in the mid-1980s,
which later were blamed for the State's low standing on National
assessment of Educational Progress exams. They are also blamed for
the fact that over half of the students admitted to the California
State University system are found to need remedial math classes
that cover elementary and intermediate algebra.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Cohen, a math professor at Stanford University, said that
students who reach the new standards will be far better prepared
mathematically than most of California pupils are today.
</P>
<P>
However, the debate is going on. Opponents say that the new
standards overemphasize basic skills while downplaying the need
for students to also understand math concepts and be able to use
then to solve problems that don't fit a standard formula.
</P>
<P>
Dan Fendel, a mathematician at the State University-San
Francisco, insisted that students who master the standards will be
adept at only part of mathematics -- number crunching. he opposed
the decision to ban the use of calculators on statewide tests --
even for computing square roots, saying that for anybody to take a
square root without a calculator is "the height of absurdity."
</P>
<P>
As teachers, scholars and political leaders across the country
have been closely following the debate, California's new standards
will set the national agenda on approaches to instruction.
</P>
<P>
The state board will also act on standards for the upper
grades, which is expected to arise equally contentious debate over
the content for the middle and high school grades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia AIDS Rate Among the Lowest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- 13 AIDS sufferers among the
total of 17 patients in Slovakia had died by the end of October,
according to statistics from the Slovakian health administration.
</P>
<P>
During the first ten months of this year, 84 Slovakians were
registered as carriers of the AIDS virus and 17 of them became the
full-blown Aids patients.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, no case of mother-to-child cross infection had been
found, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The infection rate in the country stands at a lower level among
the central eastern European countries, and for this credit is
given to measures adopted by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Slovakian government has given great attention to anti-AIDS
work. Since 1993, it has allocated several millions of crowns in
preventing and controlling the work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
