<HEADLINE> India's Reserve Bank Warns Forex Dealers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 3 (Xinhua)-- Governor of the Reserve Bank
of India (RBI) Dr. Bimal Jalan has warned banks, corporations and
other players in the foreign exchange market to behave responsibly
in their foreign exchange dealings not only in the interest of the
nation but also in their own interest.
</P>
<P>
On the background of prevailing chronic speculation in the
foreign exchange market which brought down the Indian currency
rupee to an all-time low of 39.90 to a U.S. dollar Tuesday, Jalan
said, "We have the reserve, we have the resources and we have the
will to defend the national interest and review any policy."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a specially convened press conference in Mumbai
(Bombay) Tuesday night, the RBI governor warned the players in the
market, saying "I expect them to behave responsibly."
</P>
<P>
The local foreign exchange market witnessed extreme volatility
Tuesday as the Indian rupee plunged from 39.35/45 to a dollar to
39.90/95 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Jalan said that the "external factors" were influencing the
Indian currency while the economic fundamentals remained strong.
</P>
