<HEADLINE> Jiang Calls for Closer Sino-Mexican Business Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin called here this evening for closer business links between
China and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner given in his honor by Mexican
entrepreneurs, President Jiang said the Chinese government
attaches importance to developing economic and trade ties with
Mexico and is ready to work together with the Mexican government
and businessmen for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
"Both China and Mexico are major developing countries and trade
giants in the world. Their economies are supplementary to each
other, their potentials great and the prospect bright for more
economic cooperation," Jiang told the gathering.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who arrived in this Mexican capital on Sunday night for
a state visit, urged Mexican entrepreneurs to make investments and
do business in China, and encouraged the Chinese business circles
to do the same in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Since China and Mexico established diplomatic relations in
1972, bilateral trade has grown rapidly and economic and
technological cooperation has made a "good start," Jiang said,
citing the undergoing feasibility study on bilateral cooperation
in the fields of agriculture, textile and tractor assembling.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade grew to 539 million U.S. dollars in 1996
and is expected to reach 700 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Jiang met his Mexican counterpart, Ernesto Zedillo, on Monday
to discuss bilateral ties and major international issues. The two
leaders have agreed to establish partnership of overall
cooperation well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
"Enhancing cooperation in trade and economy between China and
Mexico is not only in conformity with the fundamental interests of
the two peoples but also of great significance for the prosperity
and progress of Asia and Latin America," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president hoped Mexican businessmen would continue
to contribute to the promotion of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the Chinese economy will sustain a growth of
8 percent or above by 2000, with its export and import totaling
400 billion dollars, which will provide the world with a potential
marketplace worth 700 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
China has lowered its average import tariffs to 17 percent from
23 percent since October 1 this year, Jiang said. By 2000, it will
further decrease to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Jiang is scheduled to wind up his visit on Wednesday. During
his stay here, China and Mexico signed agreements on cooperation
in consulate affairs, sports, social science and agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
