<HEADLINE> Nepali Currency Weakens Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali currency of rupee
dipped further today by 1.5 rupees against the U.S. dollar, the
highest single-day fall since August 27.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal Rastra Bank (NRB) today refixed the buying and
selling rates of the greenback at 62.75 rupees and 63.35 rupees
respectively from Tuesday's 61.25 rupees and 61.85 rupees.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was once exchanged at a rate of 1:63.85 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As the Indian rupee fell further against the dollar Tuesday,
the Nepali rupee, which is pegged to the Indian currency at a
fixed rate of 1.6:1, has to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
This is the eighth time for the Nepali rupee to be devalued
since August 27, and the currency has fallen by 6.05 rupees since.
</P>
<P>
The NRB, the country's central bank, has so far floated 44.1
million dollars to prop up the currency.
</P>
<P>
But it was cautious this time of request for market
intervention by floating 8.25 million dollars, a local newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the request of the commercial banks is not a
genuine one but a speculative move to benefit from the ailing
rupee. It asked these banks to furnish necessary documents in
support of their demand.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the NRB intervened in the market without
hesitation at the request of the Federation of Foreign Exchange
Dealers Association, a body of 11 commercial banks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
