<HEADLINE> World Landmine Conference Opens in Ottawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 countries are
expected to send their delegations here to attend the treaty
signing conference to ban the use, production, stockpiling and
transfer of anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
Canadian External Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy told the
opening forum of the conference here today that there would be
"more opening signatures than almost any other treaty ever
negotiated."
</P>
<P>
The treaty, negotiated and adopted in Oslo, Norway in
September, will be open for signing here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
About 120 countries have agreed to sign, Axworthy said at a
media briefing held after the opening forum.
</P>
<P>
"This treaty is a testament to the political will and
determination that has inspired this process from the very
beginning," said Axworthy. A year ago he asked an anti-landmine
meeting to return to Ottawa to sign a treaty banning landmines.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the minister warned, "the ban convention will be
meaningless unless we implement it -- unless we use it as point of
departure and commit ourselves once again to work together to
eliminate all anti-personnel mines."
</P>
<P>
"The challenges are clear," Axworthy said. Participating
countries must now work together to clear mine fields, provide
assistance for victims and ensure compliance with the treaty.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Canada is expected to be the first to put its
signature on the treaty, followed by Norway and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan is scheduled to
witness the signatures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
