<HEADLINE> Indian Exporters for Further Devaluation of Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 3 (Xinhua)-- Indian exporters have time and
again urged the government to devaluate the country's currency
rupee for more exports.
</P>
<P>
"Compared to the 30-40 percent depreciation in South-East Asian
currencies, what we have got is nothing. The so-called 5-6 percent
depreciation in the Indian rupee against the greenback is not
enough," said H.R.Malik, regional director of Council for Leather
Exports.
</P>
<P>
India's exporter community is not satisfied with the current
downslide in the rupee value vis-a-vis the U.S. dollar. It wants
more depreciation. It is probable that it wants the rupee to
stabilize at the 40-41 level per U.S. dollar by the end of this
week.
</P>
<P>
"Although South-East Asian currencies have undergone
devaluation by as much as 40 percent, the Indian rupee should
settle at least at 40 rupees per U.S. dollar," said Kuldeep Singh
Chadda, western regional director of Engineering Export Promotion
Council.
</P>
<P>
The rupee came tantalizing close to 40.00 against the U.S.
dollar in early trading Tuesday but recovered on reports of the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) coming out with a package of measures
to prevent further fall of the rupee, which has slid sharply in
the past few days due to political crisis in the country and
corporate demand of U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
