<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Build Major Irrigation Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to build two major
irrigation facilities in North Western province to solve the
region's water supply problem, officials in the Irrigation and
Power Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is planning to build a reservoir, the biggest so
far to be constructed in the province, on the Deduru Oya River to
irrigate 6,800 hectares of rice land.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir is to be located about one kilometer up stream
from the Ridibendi Ella Dam on the same river. The project is
expected to inundate nearly 1,000 hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
The first stage of the project will, once completed, facilitate
irrigation of 4,800 hectares of rice land while the second stage
will provide irrigation to another 2,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The second major project is to build a 20-kilometer-long canal
to divert the water of the Maha Oya River, which divides the
Western province and the North Western province, to the Deduru Oya
Basin in the North Western province.
</P>
<P>
As the Maha Oya River has a perennial supply of water, the
diversion will help provide year-round irrigation to the basin
region, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The project costs about 600 million rupees (10 million U.S.
dollars), they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
