<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Utility Rates in Ukraine to Go up Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian Cabinet of Ministers
plans to raise funds needed for constructing nuclear power plants
by increasing the utility rates next year.
</P>
<P>
Under the new measure, the general public, along with the
industry, agriculture and transport sectors, will have to pay 4.5
percent more for electricity from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
While the last price hike by the government occurred in August
1996, the new hike would increase the cost for 10 kilowatt-hour of
electricity to about 0.86 hryvna (about 0.46 U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
Energy Minister Alexy Sheberstov said the extra funds from the
price increase would go into a special account to complete the
construction of the Khmelnytsky and Rivne nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
The two plants are to compensate for power output lost after
the Chernobyl nuclear power plant is completely shut down in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The hardest hit by the price hike is likely to be average
consumers, since most of them are already behind in their utility
bills, as they have not received their salaries for several months.
</P>
<P>
Electricity and heating arrears have reportedly grown by 4.9
percent since early November and now reach 3.4 billion hryvnas
(about 1.82 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
