<HEADLINE> Police Institutions of Mercosur Members Meet in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Directors of national police
institutions from the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) member
states, plus Bolivia and Chile, met here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the third of the kind and scheduled to last
through Thursday, was also attended by law enforcement experts
from Europe and the rest of America.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism, drug trafficking, efficiency of police forces and
measures and policies needed to curb crimes are among topics to be
discussed at the regional forum.
</P>
<P>
Guillermo Rodriguez, principal of the National School of Police
of Uruguay, said the event would establish common criteria and
procedures to fight crimes.
</P>
<P>
Joint actions are necessary, he said, explaining that the
integration process, by opening the borders, will make it easier
for organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, South America's largest trade bloc, groups Brazil,
Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay, with Chile and Bolivia as
associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
