<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Businesses Urge More Deregulation by Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- American businesses in Thailand
have urged the country to further deregulate and curb corruption
in its efforts to lure more foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The American Chamber of Commerce in Thailand recommended that
the Thai government attracts more investments in high-tech
industries and services to regain the country's economic growth
momentum.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Tuesday and available today, the
chamber said, "Thailand, no longer able to rely on inexpensive
skilled labor as the lure for foreign investors, must change its
business climate to attract investments in the more value-added
industries."
</P>
<P>
Among the chamber's recommendations, made to protect American
businesses from Thailand's economic crisis, are scrapping the
alien business law; removing all restrictions on foreign ownership
of assets, including real estate; allowing unrestricted foreign
participation in the service sector; lifting value-added tax on
raw materials; stopping the practices of "under-the-table"
payments; relaxing regulations on visas and work permits;
simplifying customs procedures and eliminating corruption.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that lifting all discriminatory barriers to
foreign ownership of financial assets will accelerate the process
of recapitalizing not only in the service sector but also in other
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recommendations, Thai Deputy Prime Minister
in Charge of Economic Matters Supachai Panitchpakdi admitted that
the Alien Business Law, imposed in 1972 to protect Thai investors,
does not promote competition and that the country has to
deregulate to comply with World Trade Organization agreements.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Alien Business Law may be replaced by other
laws giving foreigners "100 percent freedom" to do business in
Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Tackle Rural Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Brazil will launch an
education program for peasants next year, Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso said today.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly broadcast, Cardoso said the plan will bring
training to 200,000 rural families of the country.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso hoped that with the help of the 14,000 university
teachers involved in the program, all Brazilian peasants would
learn to read and write, and be skilled in elementary arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
Only knowledge and literacy were passports for a better life,
he said. With these, peasants would have more opportunities to use
modern techniques of cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to be carried out by the Ministries of Education,
Agrarian Reform and universities.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 32.77 million illiterate people in Brazil live in
rural areas, and account for 20 percent of the country's total
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
