<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno: No Independent Counsel to Probe Clinton, Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno today rejected seeking an independent counsel to investigate
telephone fund raising by President Bill Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
"I have determined there are no reasonable grounds to believe
that further investigation is warranted of allegations that the
president violated federal law by making fund-raising telephone
calls from the White House," Reno said in papers filed with a
special three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, no independent counsel needs to be appointed," Reno
said in the document.
</P>
<P>
Investigation found that Clinton made telephone calls from the
White House relating to potential fund-raising solicitations on
only three occasions, she said. These calls were made from the
private residential portion of the White House and thus were
outside the scope of the law at issue.
</P>
<P>
Reno said, the evidence that Gore may have violated (the law)
is "insufficient to warrant further investigation."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said later in the day that Reno followed the proper
process in deciding not to appoint a special prosecutor to
investigate campaign fund raising by him and Gore.
</P>
<P>
"The attorney general made her decision based on a careful
review of the law and the facts and that's as it should be,"
Clinton said in a statement issued by the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
