<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Expects Budget Deficit in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The documents showed that the government may not be able to
post a budget surplus in 1998 as it hopes but may instead incur a
4.29 billion peso (126 million U.S. dollars) shortfall.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time since 1994 that the national
government will suffer a budget shortfall, which happens when cash
expenditures exceed revenues.
</P>
<P>
The expected budget deficit for 1998 was agreed upon recently
by the government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) as
part of the fiscal program for 1998.
</P>
<P>
An IMF team has just concluded its review of the country's
economic performance for the first three quarters of 1997. A
meeting between the team and the Philippines' economic officials
found that the country may suffer a deficit in 1998 due to an
expected economic slow-down.
</P>
<P>
The government originally set a budget surplus target of 13
billion pesos (492 million dollars) for 1998, but last month
revised it down to only 7 billion pesos (205 million dollars)
considering the adverse impact of a region-wide financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But economists said there's still a chance the government may
manage a budget surplus next year if its tax reform law yields a
significant sum of net revenue and if state-owned assets such as
the National Power Corp. are privatized.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been in perennial budget deficit since the
early 1970s. It managed to bring this to an end only in 1994 when
the government posted a surplus of 16.3 billion pesos (617 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government was able to sustain the surplus in the next two
years -- 11.1 billion pesos (421 million dollars) in 1995 and 6.3
billion pesos (239 million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
For 1997, the government hoped to obtain seven to 13 billion
pesos in budget surplus. But the hope is shaky as the government's
cash position for the first 10 months of the year is in the red to
the tune of 2.3 billion pesos (69.7 million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0257 </DOCNO>
