<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Exports Up 11 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's export earnings
in the first eight months of the year rose by 11.4 percent over
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Exports amounted to 3.41 billion U.S. dollars from January to
August, compared with 3.06 billion dollars a year earlier, the
Ministry of Foreign Trade said today.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country also earned foreign currencies worth
587 million dollars from tourism over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Trade Ministry's goal for the year in foreign
currency earnings is 4.83 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of all exports, manufactured products were the most dynamic in
the eight-month period, with a sales growth of 71 percent,
followed by cattle and fishing products.
</P>
<P>
The United States remains the single most important overseas
market for Costa Rica, as it is the destination for 50 percent of
this Central American country's exports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the second and third markets for Costa Rican
products are Europe and Central America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
