<HEADLINE> Manila Agrees on Truce for Release of Policemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The NPA may release the two hostages, who were captured early
last month, to Lower House Speaker Jose de Venecia and Solicitor
General Silvestre Bello, local newspaper the Manila Chronicle
today quoted a senior military official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces Chief of Staff Gen. Arnulfo Acedera told reporters
Tuesday that Police Chief Inspector Rene Francisco and Army
Sergeant Joanquin Melad might be released today.
</P>
<P>
Acedera said the earlier spate of attacks launched by the NPA
against the military and the police is only a ploy to support its
political wing the National Democratic Front (NDF) in peace
negotiations with the government.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia was quoted as saying the government is working for
the implementation of an extended ceasefire until Christmas in
order to provide a conducive atmosphere for resuming peace talks
with the NDF.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the peace talks in the Netherlands, where
many NDF leaders are living in exile, was tentatively scheduled on
December 8.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia said he had been assured by NDF leader Jose Sison
over telephone last Saturday that the two hostages will be
released safely and be turned over to the house speaker.
</P>
<P>
The military and the national police have agreed to temporarily
halt operations against the NPA in northern Philippines to
facilitate the release of the two captives.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, an alliance of leftists created in late 1960s, has
fought the government for more than three decades. The NDF's
insurgency peaked during the mid-1980s with its military arm, the
NPA, boasting a membership of 25,000.
</P>
<P>
Military estimates placed the current membership of the NPA at
about 8,000. The NPA is still active in some parts of the country.
 
</P>
