<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Refuses to Sign Mine Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine will not be among the
first batch to sign the Convention to Ban Anti-Personnel Mines,
the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry announced today.
</P>
<P>
A ministry spokesman told a news briefing that Ukraine rejected
the signing because the destruction of anti-personnel weapons
needed a large amount of money and Ukraine could not afford the
financial burden.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman did not rule out a possible signing in the future.
</P>
<P>
A three-day conference on the land mines ban is being held in
Ottawa, Canada, and most of the participating countries are
expected to sign the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, signatories will be required to destroy their
reserves of land mines within four years.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Ukraine stopped manufacturing mines and had
suspended mine exports since 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Banks Offer Light on Nazi Gold Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Germany's two largest commercial
banks, the Deutsche Bank and the Dresdner Bank, said today they
would help clarify allegations that they had held some of the
Jewish gold robbed by German Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made in reaction to a German television
report on Monday that part of about two tons of gold German Nazis
grabbed from eastern European Jews between 1942 and 1945 had been
transferred to the Deutsche Bank and the Dresdner Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the ARD television network, the conclusion was
drawn from microfilm found in Vienna last week, which included
some photocopies of original documents and files of the Nazi
central bank, the Reichsbank.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Reichsbank had melted the robbed gold into
bullion and sold about 650 kilogrammes to the Deutsche Bank and
about 313 kilogrammes to the Dresdner Bank.
</P>
<P>
The two German banks said they had no knowledge of the dealing
and would be willing to clarify the issue.
</P>
<P>
"We are interested in seeking a clarification," a Deutsche Bank
spokesman said in Frankfurt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
