<HEADLINE> Beijing Newspapers Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- One of China's better-known coal mines, the Kailuan Coal
Mining Administration, has been showing a profit for the past
three years, and has been setting a good example for state-owned
enterprises nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The administration in north China was running in the red for
eight years before 1994. The situation began to change
after it started allowing its 19 subsidiary mines to make their
own business decisions in 1993, in such areas as production,
operation, materials purchase, marketing, personnel and wages.
</P>
<P>
-- Grain output in China for 1997 is expected to be the same as
last year, announced the Agriculture Ministry at a national
agriculture conference opened in Hefei yesterday.
</P>
<P>
There will be record high grain reserves as well, and a balance
between supply and demand. There will be more cotton this year,
but output of oil-bearing crops will drop a bit. Added value of
rural enterprises will be up 18 percent from last year. And
farmers' incomes will grow by 4 percent, when adjusted for
inflation.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his Mexican
counterpart, Ernesto Zedillo, Monday agreed that China and Mexico
should establish a partnership of all-round cooperation crossing
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reached the agreement during their talks at the
presidential residence in Mexico City. They maintained that such a
relationship is of great importance in enhancing the overall
strength of developing countries, and in establishing a new
international political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin is to attend informal summit
meetings between China and the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) in Malaysia on December 14, at the invitation of
Dr. Mahathir Mohammed, rotating chairman of ASEAN and prime
minister of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
-- The Nanning-Kunming Railway, which entered operations
yesterday, has brought great change to the once isolated lives of
minority ethnic groups in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the railway created tens of thousands of jobs
for local residents in southwestern Guizhou Province, and enabled
more than 520,000 people to shake off poverty during the 1993-1996
period, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign-invested firms' imports of capital goods will
remain duty-free until these companies reach their import ceilings
determined by their respective investment totals.
</P>
<P>
The State Council approved the policy, which applies to firms
approved by China before March 31,1996, announced the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese side will abide by the spirit of the
Sino-British Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong, and
will work with the British side to fulfill the tasks of the
Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG) over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Wang Guisheng, China's chief JLG representative,
made the remarks yesterday during the two-day 41st session of the
JLG, the group's first meeting since Hong Kong's return to the
motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
