<HEADLINE> Cuba, US Resume Negotiations on Migration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuba and the United States today
started their 8th round of talks on immigration in Havana.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban delegation was headed by Ricardo Alarcon, president
of the National Assembly of the People's Power, and the U.S. by
Undersecretary of State John Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
Before the talks, Alarcon told reporters that some Cubans were
still trying to go to the United States illegally, violating the
treaties signed by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the U.S. intention to broadcast a TV program from
Miami to Cuba, which did not tally with the accord on a joint
solution to the broadcasting between the two nations signed in
1987. The Cuban official described the action as provocative.
</P>
<P>
The United States is taking strict measures to prevent Cubans
from traveling there, Alarcon said, most of the Cubans who wish to
go to the United States just want to visit their relatives and not
to emigrate.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Cuban and U.S. officials will analyze
migratory agreements signed by the two countries in September 1994
and May 1995.
</P>
<P>
The last round of negotiations was held in July 1997 in New
York. 
</P>
