<HEADLINE> Sinopec to Get 50 Million Dollars in Syndicated Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 3 (Xinhua) -- China Petrochemical Corp
(Sinopec) received here Tuesday international syndicated loans
involving 50 million U.S. dollars, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The money will fund technical innovations on the refining
equipment of Sinopec's subsidiaries located in coastal areas,
which are engaged in processing imported oil.
</P>
<P>
The financial institutions signing the agreement on the
syndicated loans are Nippon Life Insurance Co., Sumitomo Bank and
Yamaguchi Bank.
</P>
<P>
The loans are arranged on a favorable interest rate with a
tenure of eight years and a grace period of four year. The
favorable terms are comparable to those offered by foreign banks
to State-owned commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The successful arrangement of the loan marks a new level in the
development of cooperation between Sinopec and the international
financial community, said Wang Jiming, vice-president of the
company.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, Sinopec has raised 8.36 billion
U.S. dollars in overseas funds for a number of its petrochemical
projects, including foreign governmental and commercial loans,
export credit and international rent. 
</P>
