<HEADLINE> Allen Johnson, Marion Jones Win Owens Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Allen Johnson and Marion
Jones, the only two double gold medalists at this year's world
outdoor championships, were named as the winners of the 1997 Jesse
Owens Award.
</P>
<P>
The Owens Award is presented annually by USA Track and Field to
the United States' top male and female performers. The
announcement came on the opening day of USATF's annual convention.
</P>
<P>
Johnson and Jones will formally receive their awards at a
banquet Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Johnson proved himself the world's best 110-meter hurdler for
the third straight year by winning the world championship at
Athens in 12.93 seconds, the year's fastest time. He also won gold
at the 1996 Olympics and at the 1995 worlds.
</P>
<P>
He earned a second gold at Athens by running a leg on the
1,600-meter relay in a preliminary round after Michael Johnson and
Butch Reynolds were injured.
</P>
<P>
Johnson received 1,962 votes ahead of Maurice Greene, the
100-meter world champion, 1,902 points. World discus champion John
Godina was third. Three-time Owens winner Michael Johnson finished
fourth.
</P>
<P>
Jones won the 100 and long jump at the USA Championships, then
took gold at Athens in the 100 and the 400 relay. She had 1997
world-best times of 10.76 in the 100 and 21.76 in the 200, as well
as an American season best of 22 feet, 7 inches, in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
In the voting, Jones received 2,409 points, 644 more than
runner-up Jearl Miles-Clark, the 400 bronze medalist at the
worlds. Regina Jacobs, the 1,500 silver medalist at Athens, was
third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
