<HEADLINE> Clinton not to Change Planned Visit to India, Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton will
not change his original plan to visit India and Pakistan next year
despite possible changes of leadership in both countries, the
White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The president often travels to countries which are undergoing
changes of leadership," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.
"I'm not aware of any change in the president's plans to travel
next year."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States hopes the visit would be "fruitful
and productive from the viewpoint of engaging with the leadership
of both countries."
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, India's government fell when Inder Kumar Gujral's
14-party United Front Coalition broke apart. And there will be an
election. And in Pakistan, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and
President Farooq Ahmed Leghari are not on good terms.
</P>
<P>
The White House has not specified the timing of the trip, that
could leave room for events in both countries to cool. 
</P>
