<HEADLINE> Reno Decides not to Seek Outside Counsel for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno Tuesday decided not to seek an independent counsel to
investigate fund-raising phone calls by President Bill Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore, Justice Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials said Reno decided that there exist no reasonable
grounds under the law to warrant further investigation by an
outside prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
Reno followed the advice of Justice Department prosecutors on
the task force investigating alleged campaign finance violations.
</P>
<P>
She turned down the recommendation of FBI Director Louis Freeh,
who had been trying to persuade her to go forward with
investigation by an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
Gore had admitted making more than 40 phone calls asking for
campaign donations from the White House. Clinton said he did not
remember, but had not ruled out making such calls between 1994 and
1996.  
