<HEADLINE> UK Business People Are Serious about Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The British business people "are
serious about China and about building a constructive and dynamic
economic partnership with China," said a senior cabinet minister
here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Margaret Beckett, President of the Board of Trade, made these
remarks while she was speaking to several hundred business people
from all over Britain.
</P>
<P>
Beckett said that Britain is the largest European investor in
China and that is something for which Britain must take some
credit.
</P>
<P>
Beckett stressed, even though exports to China have gone up by
over 20 per cent this year at a time when its trade with most
other Asia Pacific markets has remained broadly static, there is
still so much more that Britain could do.
</P>
<P>
Referring to her forthcoming visit to China, Beckett said, it
is an important visit for two main reasons:
</P>
<P>
First, it will be the first high-level trade focused visit to
China since the Labor Government took office in May.
</P>
<P>
Second, it will be the first visit of this kind to China since
the transfer of sovereignty of Hong Kong at the end of last June.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the impact of the financial tubulence in the Asia
Pacific and the way China is dealing with it, Beckett said, "China
has so far managed to weather these storms."
</P>
<P>
"It has also demonstrated its economic maturity in the way in
which it did not interfere directly in Hong Kong when the markets
there were so volatile," she added.
</P>
<P>
On China's economic reform achievements, Beckett said, China
has over the last two years confounded many economic pundits who
predicted that its levels of growth were not sustainable and that
it was bound to suffer a hard economic landing.
</P>
<P>
It is now commonly agreed, Beckett said, within the first two
decades of the next century China could well become the largest
economy in the world.
</P>
<P>
She said, "It is therefore a market which not only none of us
should ignore but to which we should pay ever closer and more
focused attention." 
</P>
</TEXT>
