<HEADLINE> U.S. Advises Halt of War of Words over Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 2 (Xinhua) -- the United States on Tuesday
called on Israel and the Palestinians to stop war of words about
unilateral takeovers on the West Bank and deal with the
territory's future at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said the war of words
between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat ad Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu was neither constructive nor helpful to Middle
East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Arafat said he would declare a Palestinian state in
1999 if Israel fails to meet a May 1999 deadline for a final
agreement. And an adviser to Netanyahu reacted on Monday that the
Israeli leader would "feel free" to annex the West Bank if Arafat
unilaterally declares statehood there and in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the two sides should not discuss the status of the
territories until they start so-called "final status" talks.
</P>
<P>
"None of this rhetoric is very helpful to the peace process. We
believe that issues reserved for permanent status, such as the
question of sovereignty and borders, need to be addressed in the
permanent status negotiations, which we are trying very hard to
reach," he told reporters at a regular briefing.  
</P>
