<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Zambian President Reshuffles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba today announced a surprising reshuffle concerning
Vice-president Brigade General Godfrey Miyanda and defense
minister as well as the country's heads of armed forces.
</P>
<P>
According to Chiluba's reshuffle arrangements, which is the
first since he was reelected in 1996, Miyanda was demoted to be
education minister and former defense minister Benjamin Mwila
became energy minister.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also dismissed army commander Nobby Shimbeye from
office and ordered air force commander Ronald Shinkapwasha to
resign.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held in the State House today, Chiluba
justified his decision as "necessary" to "reinforce and
rejuvenate" the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
However, Zambian observers believed that the move is an
immediate consequence of the abortive military coup, which took
place on October 28 in order to overthrow the Chiluba government.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that Miyanda, Mwila, Shimbeye and Shinkapwasha
did not perform well during the four-hour coup. After the coup
was reported, Miyanda, who was then in England to attend the
summit meeting of the Commonwealth members, did not strongly
condemn the coup attempt and said something that was inconsistent
with Chiluba's remarks.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that the coup's failure showed that his
government is in firm control of the country and the confidence
of domestic and foreign investors in Zambia's political stability
can not be damaged. While Miyanda said that it will take a long
time for the investors to resume investment in the poor country.
</P>
<P>
As for the army leaders, they should be blamed for the
military coup. They neither prevented it from taking place nor
played an effective role in cracking down the coupists as Major
General Solomon Mumbi did, who was the deputy army commander and
promoted to replace Shimbeye.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, there are lingering rumors to the effect that the
Zambian military supported Angola's former opposition UNITA (the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola) by
airlifting arms to them. This allegation has made the Chiluba
government embarrassed and deteriorated the relations between the
two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The other reason, according to the observers here, to push
Chiluba for the shake-up is the escalating party strife. As time
has passed, the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD)
members have been struggling clandestinely for the candidature of
the presidential election in 2001 when Chiluba's second term
expires.
</P>
<P>
In the face of political impasse with the country's opposition
party and growing quarrels in the ruling MMD, Chiluba has to
choose to protect the partisan interests at the expense of some
of his disobedient colleagues in order to strengthen the party's
unity and ensure its ruling position after 2001.
</P>
<P>
However, Chiluba's move is characterized remarkably in two
aspects. Although most of the ministerial portfolios have been
affected in the shake-up, none of the bureaucrats have been
dismissed. On the other hand, Chiluba treated the demoted ranks
softly by giving them other junior or unimportant posts.
</P>
<P>
This kind of "soft treatment" is widely believed as a smart
tactic to prevent unexpected turmoils in the country.
</P>
<P>
In any event, Chiluba is determined by the "necessary" move to
redress the serious social and political problems encountered by
his MMD government. It will undoubtedly have meaningful impact on
the country's political progress as well as economic reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
