<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Members Agree on New Command Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana today claimed that the Western military alliance has agreed
on its new command structure after two major disputes were ironed
out via mutual agreements.
</P>
<P>
Solana described as "historic" the agreement which was approved
by all the 16 allies including France and Spain though both are
still outside the NATO integrated military command.
</P>
<P>
He said that the new command structure will be militarily
effective and functional and considerably streamlined.
</P>
<P>
NATO plans to reduce its regional headquarters from 65 to 20
and make regional headquarters more international by manning
regional headquarters with up to 50 percent of officers from
countries other than the host country.
</P>
<P>
"It will fully support enlargement and greater involvement by
partners and will be more cost-effective. It will also support the
European Security and Defense Identity," said Solana. He added
that the alliance will start working on the implementation of the
new command structure.
</P>
<P>
Regional disputes have been bottlenecking NATO's long-planned
internal adaptation.
</P>
<P>
Just prior to the year-end meeting of NATO defense ministers,
Greece and Turkey reached agreement on the eastern Aegean command
issue while Britain and Spain agreed on the Gibraltar command.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief hailed the agreement between Greece and Turkey
as a historic breakthrough overcoming differences that go back
almost 40 years. "It will make NATO more effective in the eastern
Aegean, a region of key strategic significance for all allies," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that the agreement between Britain and Spain has a
direct bearing on the new command structure and that Spain is
intended to re-join the integrated command structure in the very
near future.
</P>
<P>
Like France, Spain pulled out of the NATO integrated command
due to a row with Britain over Gibraltar. It has since been
demanding that the regional command headquarters be moved to
Madrid in exchange for softening its approach toward Gibraltar, a
military installation still held by the Britons.
</P>
<P>
Though France made it well known at the unofficial meeting of
NATO defense ministers at Maastricht in early October this year
that it will remain outside the NATO integrated command, it
expressed its intention at the Brussels meeting today that it
will continue to be involved in the work on the internal
adaptation of the alliance military structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Says Visit to Mexico Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here today that his visit to Mexico was a success and
achieved desired results.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Televisa, Mexico's largest television
station, Jiang said the visit, which was a success, has achieved
the objectives of deepening understanding, enhancing friendship,
looking forward to the future and developing cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang arrived in Mexico Monday for a four-day state visit, the
first ever made by a Chinese head of state.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Televisa that he and his Mexican counterpart,
Ernesto Zedillo, had an in-depth exchange of views and reached an
extensive consensus on bilateral relationship and international
issues.
</P>
<P>
"President Zedillo and I are old friends, and this is our fifth
meeting. Our talks have yielded positive results. Tomorrow, I will
meet people from Mexico's political and business sectors. Through
the visit, I have learned more about Mexico, the Latin American
country with a civilization of long standing," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about China's application for the membership of the World
Trade Organization (WTO), Jiang said China is always ready to
join the world trade group. As an international trade
organization, the WTO should enjoy universal participation, Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that without China, the world's largest developing
country and a major exporter, the WTO will be incomplete.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed that China must be accepted by the WTO as a
developing country.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the president said, China is making efforts
to meet the minimum requirements set by the WTO.
</P>
<P>
As for the current financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, Jiang
said that a worldwide financial crisis is not a sudden
incident. Mexico was hit by the peso crisis in 1994-95, he added,
but the Mexican government handled the crisis properly and
solved it successfully.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China's economy has maintained a sustained and
stable growth in recent years. Financial market is emerging in
China but still at the primary stage.
</P>
<P>
As for Hong Kong's financial market, Jiang said he is full of
confidence that it will have a bright future because it enjoys a
sound legal and management system.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, the Chinese government resumed the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong. A stable economy on the mainland of
China would help maintain a stable financial market in Hong Kong,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Taiwan issue, Jiang stressed that Taiwan is
an integral part of the Chinese territory. The Chinese government
has always adopted a consistent policy of peaceful reunification
and one country, two systems.
</P>
<P>
He added that his eight-point-proposal on the Taiwan question
issued in 1995 remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government always welcomes the Taiwan authorities
coming back to the policy of one China and peaceful reunification,
so as to realize the reunification of the motherland through
political dialog, Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
