<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Should not Hinder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran stressed today that to
reduce the emission of greenhouse gases worldwide should in no way
hinder the pace of progress of developing countries, the Iranian
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Various measures to curb the emission of greenhouse gases,
notably carbon dioxide, should not deprive the developing
countries of their right to development, said Iran's Vice
President and Head of the Environmental Protection Organization
Masoumeh Ebtekar.
</P>
<P>
She was leaving for Kyoto, Japan to attend a conference on
greenhouse effect and global warming.
</P>
<P>
She said the emission of greenhouse gases by developing
countries is much lower than that by developed countries, which
have been demanded and are obliged to make greater efforts in
curbing global warming caused by greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
She said that Iran, along with other developing countries,
should form a definite stance on the deadline to determine the
types of greenhouse gases that are posing threats to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the progress made by developing countries is
of great value and a key factor in protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
Iran takes into account environmental factors in formulating
its development programs, and Iran exploits its resources in the
most appropriate way, Ebtekar said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Iran as a developing country would announce its
policy on the issue of greenhouse effect at the Kyoto conference.
</P>
<P>
Top environmental experts and officials from 180 countries and
regions attend the conference which started on Monday and would
last till December 11. It is the third such meeting focusing on
climatic changes and their effect on world environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
