<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Pays Short Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa paid a short visit to Saudi Arabia today to deliver a
letter from Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to King Fahd Bin
Abdel Aziz dealing with strains in Egyptian-Qatari relations.
</P>
<P>
The letter came in reply to King Fahd's message to Mubarak
conveyed by Saudi Minister of State Abdel Aziz al-Khuwaiter
earlier today on the situation in the Arab and Gulf arenas,
particularly the growing tension between Egypt and Qatar,
according to reports by Kuwait News Agency from Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
A row was kicked up between Egypt and Qatar over Qatari
charges that Egypt had plotted the 1996 coup attempt trying to
overthrow the ruler of the Gulf state, but Egypt refused the
charges and demanded an explanation. Qatar opened trial last
Wednesday of 110 people charged with the coup attempt which added
fuel to the row.
</P>
<P>
Sources believe the letter was related to mediation efforts
by Riyadh to mend fences between Cairo and Doha.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Riyadh, Moussa also met the Saudi Crown
Prince and deputy Prime Minister Prince Abdallah IBn Abdul-Aziz.
Political sources were quoted as saying that Moussa expressed his
country's points of view on the current icy Egyptian-Qatari
relations and asserted that Cairo does not want to escalate the
crisis and is keen to maintain relations with Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from Doha said the Amir of Qatar Sheikh
Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani would head to Jeddah, Saudi Arabia,
Wednesday for a similar short visit during which he is expected
to hold talks with King Fahd on means of settling the disputes.
</P>
