<HEADLINE> Nigerian Warships Sent to S. Leone Water, Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Three Nigerian warships are on
their way to the coast of Sierra Leone one day after the west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) threatened to tighten
blockade on that country on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement today, the military junta in Freetown
said that the Nigerian contingent in ECOMOG based in Liberia has
decided to send naval vessels to the territorial waters of Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
Up to last night, the vessels were 70 nautical miles off the
Sierra Leonean coast, the statement said, quoted by the British
Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone has been under economic sanctions and embargo
imposed by west African countries and the United Nations not long
after the coup ousted the civilian government of president Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah on May 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the military junta has signed a peace accord and
agreed to step down by April next year, agreement has not yet
been reached as to whether the armed forces of Sierra Leone
should be disarmed, among other important issues.
</P>
<P>
As last week's talks between west African countries and the
junta on the implementation of the peace plan went in deadlock,
ECOMOG force commander Major-general Victor Malu has vowed to
increase military pressure on the junta to bring it back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ECOMOG has begun a phased pullout of its troops
from Liberia where the force disarmed all warring factions and
ensured the post-war election last July.
</P>
<P>
It is unknown whether the soldiers back from Liberia will be
transferred to Sierra Leone to join in the enforcement of the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
However, reacting to the news of the arrival of Nigerian
warships, a manager in Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone,
described the whole thing as blackmail.
</P>
<P>
The economic community of west African states has lost its
sense of direction on the Sierra Leone peace process, he said,
adding that it is up to the people of Sierra Leone to judge the
sitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
