<HEADLINE> Greece Expresses Satisfaction Over NATO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Greece today expressed
satisfaction over the agreement reached in Brussels on the new
structure of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Athens' satisfaction came from the agreement that there will be
no discussion at the present time on matters related to the
operation of NATO's new units, but only about their formation,
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today.
</P>
<P>
German General Klaus Naumann, head of NATO's military
committee, announced in Brussels Monday night that Greece and
Turkey, both NATO members, had reached an agreement on a
decades-old dispute concerning the use of air space over the
Aegean Sea. He also said that the agreement included all military
aspects of the alliance's new command structure.
</P>
<P>
Reppas emphasized that Greece will be able to exercise its
sovereign rights within the framework of the new structure and has
the power to safeguard them.
</P>
<P>
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis today described the
agreement on NATO's new structure as "a positive development."
</P>
<P>
The agreement did not pertain to air space over the Aegean Sea,
he said in Paris, adding that his country agreed with the new
structure because it facilitated cooperation between the
alliance's member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
