<HEADLINE> Palestinians Yet to Response to Israel's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) said here today
that the Palestinians have not yet formulated their response to
Israeli Cabinet decision on a conditional troops' withdrawal from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy in
Jerusalem, Abbas told reporters that the PNA is waiting for
Israeli government's clear decision on the actual scope of further
pull-back.
</P>
<P>
Levy said that Israel's four-member ministerial team, which is
authorized to draw up the requisite maps and timetable for the
implementation of the cabinet's decision, would reach a conclusion
as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet endorsed Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
proposal last Sunday that Israel implement further redeployment
on condition that PNA fulfills its commitments appended to the
Hebron accord signed by two sides last January.
</P>
<P>
PNA had mixed reactions to the Israeli decision. Several
Palestinian officials charged that the plan is "a continuation of
the Israeli government's attempt to evade the agreement on further
redeployment."
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman, Marwan Kanafani said, "the decision to
redeploy is encouraging, but some of the terms mentioned cause us
to be skeptical to the (Israeli) government's sincerity in
implementing the redeployment."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian senior negotiator Saeb Erekat charged that the PNA
had not received any official statement from the Israeli
government and would comment only when such a statement was
received. 
</P>
</TEXT>
