<HEADLINE> Round-up: United Nations Urged to Reinvigorate Stalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The time has come for
the United Nations to reinvigorate the stalled Middle East peace
process since the United States is reluctant to persuade the
Israeli Government to fulfill its obligations, the General
Assembly has been told as it began its consideration of the
question of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Farouk Kaddoumi, Chairman of Palestinian Observer Delegation,
said the peace process had reached an impasse due to the Israeli
Government's provocative acts. On the issue of Jerusalem, Israel
was challenging the international community and rejecting the
implementation of the United Nations resolutions. The blockade of
the occupied Palestinian territories prevented entry and departure
of people, food and materials and increased unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said the United States was not an effective
player. Although it was the main sponsor of the peace process, it
was reluctant to persuade the Israeli Government to fulfill its
obligations. Rather than play a vital role, the United States
hesitated, giving Israel time to confiscate more land, build more
settlements and intensify their blockade.
</P>
<P>
He said the time had come for the United Nations, which has a
history of addressing other international issues, to preserve
the peace process. For the United Nations to be effective, the
requirements for peace and security must be respected by all
member states.
</P>
<P>
Makarim Wibisono of Indonesia said it was appalling that
Israeli authorities were perpetuating policies that could only
bring disastrous consequences. The expansion of settlements in
and around Jabal Abu Ghneim was foremost among those policies
and was compounded by other "untenable actions", including the
demolition of properties, closures and the denial of residency
rights to Palestinians to live in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said such acts had dealt a serious blow to the peace
process and inflamed passions throughout the occupied
territories and around the world. The Israeli Government could
not hide behind the "flimsy pretext" of security consideration
to justify its actions against the entire people, nor could it
rationalize intimidation, repression and persecution.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that peace and security were intertwined and could
not be based on the usurpation of the basic rights of the
Palestinian people. Israel must be urged to fulfill legal
commitments with consistency and fairness.
</P>
<P>
The delegate said the United Nations and its agencies had a
central role to play in alleviating the plight of the
Palestinian people and assisting in nation-building.
</P>
<P>
Abdelkader Mesdoua of Algeria said the serious impasse facing
the Middle East peace process was due primarily to the
intransigent position of the current Israeli Government. Israel had
tried to undermine the peace process by refusing to withdraw from
Palestinian territories, continuing its attempts of settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
The delegate said the United Nations responsibility for
Palestine remained as long as the cause of the Palestinian people
remained.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Jassim Samhan Al-Nuatt of United Arab Emirates said
the United Nations resolutions, the Madrid and other agreements,
and efforts by states and international organizations had met
with expansion and repression carried out by Israel in the
occupied Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
He said the international community, specially the United
Nations must pressure Israel to yield to legality which required
the dismantling of settlements and the opening or reopening of
the Gaza airport and port, the freeing of all Palestinian people
and the redeployment of Israeli forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
