<HEADLINE> Mubarak's Sons Drop Libel Case Against Saudi Papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak's two sons have agreed to drop a lawsuit against six
journalists of a Saudi daily, one of the largest in the Arab world
and a sister newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency reported that Gamal Mubarak held a
"cordial" meeting senior officials of the London-based Asharq
al-Awsat and Al-Jadida on Sunday and decided to withdraw the court
case in which the six journalists have been found guilty of
libeling.
</P>
<P>
The daily, owned by the Saudi royal family, agreed to reopen
its office in Cairo which was closed during the case.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, Mubarak's two sons said the
Saudis presented an apology and expressed great regret for "the
gross mistake" made by the two newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached agreement "in consideration of the close
and cordial relations between the people and governments of Egypt
and Saudi Arabia," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Asharq al-Awsat ran a promotion for a forthcoming story in
Al-Jadida on allegations that Alaa and Gamal, Mubarak's two sons,
used their father's position to further business dealings. This,
the statement said, did great harm to the brothers by subjecting
them to "unfounded and untrue actions" and "biased and false
rumors."
</P>
<P>
However, the damaging story never came out. The publishers said
they destroyed all 120,000 issues of Al-Jadida hours before it hit
newsstands and later ran a full-page apology. They also fired two
of the accused journalists.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, the brothers sued six journalists from the daily
and weekly, and in mid-September a Cairo court sentenced in
absentia five, including the two Saudi publishers and
editor-in-chief of Asharq Al-Awsat, to one year in prison with
hard labor for libeling.
</P>
<P>
The sixth, an Egyptian, attended the trial and got six months
in prison. The journalists appealed.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
left here today for Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, hours after President
Mubarak received a message from King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
It is yet unknown whether Moussa's lightning visit has
something to do with the development of the libeling case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
