<DOCNO> XIE19971203.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-02 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Wins Bid to Host 1998 Interpol Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 2 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has won the bid to host the
International Criminal Police Organization (Interpol) Conference
next year, a chance to give a face-lift of its security, the
Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based criminal police group is aimed at developing a
worldwide network to prevent and fight crimes with the joint
effort of its 188 member states.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by Interpol's Cairo office today said that
the international group approved Egypt's hosting of the event in
"appreciation of its strong stance against any criminal acts."
</P>
<P>
"It also proves the genuine stability enjoyed by Egypt despite
rare acts perpetrated by a small minority," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was awarded the opportunity after beating rivals of
Australia, South Korea and Greece which had all submitted their
offers to be the host.
</P>
<P>
The Interpol conference is to deal with a number of topics
including the organization's new strategy for the coming century,
development of fight against criminal gangs, and stepping up
confrontation with international terrorism and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
This would be the first time for Egypt to host meetings of the
Interpol, which was set up in Vienna, Austria, in 1923 with only
seven member states.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, stricken by a new wave of Islamic militant insurgency
and attacks this year, has launched an all-out campaign to fight
terrorism and overhaul security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
