<HEADLINE> Two Cypriot Communities Urged to Cooperate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Commissioner of the
European Union (EU) for External Relations Hans Van den Broek
today urged the two communities of Cyprus to cooperate in the
issue of accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held here at the end of his
visit to the island, Van den Broek said that the two communities
will have to work out a formula regarding the participation the
Turkish Cypriots in the talks, which he said can facilitate
political solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The EU commissioner, arriving here Monday, discussed separately
with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash ways of ensuring both communities are represented in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an eastern Mediterranean island, submitted in 1990 its
application for full membership to the EU, which decided in March
1995 to start talks with Cyprus early next year.
</P>
<P>
But EU's decision was rejected by Denktash, who walked out of
talks with Clerides last August and demanded the EU freeze the
plan.
</P>
<P>
"When we talk about Cyprus becoming a member of the EU, then
the benefits, the rights and the obligations should apply to both
communities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it will be desirable and useful for the two communities
to take advantage of the accession talks "to create more
understanding".
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and a Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
took over the northern third of the island following a failed
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the ties between the European Union and Turkey,
Van den Broek described it as "an important partner" of the EU.
</P>
<P>
However, he said it is still premature for the EU to accept
Turkey as a member.
</P>
<P>
"But we have at the same time given the very clear intention
to work together with them, to dialogue with them to enhance the
process toward their integration into the EU," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
