<HEADLINE> France Offers S. Africa Defense Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- France today presented a
comprehensive military equipment package proposal to South
Africa, including favourable interest rate, long-term payment and
extensive technology exchange.
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador Tristan D'Albis told a press conference on
board the French Surcouf frigatre in Cape Town harbor that the
proposal were specifically adapted to South African needs and
entailed cooperation agreements.
</P>
<P>
The proposals to provide for South African defense needs
include four corvettes, four to six maritime patrol helicopters,
60 light utility helicopters, 90 main battle tanks, 48 Mirage
2000 light fighter aircrafts and four new generation submarines.
</P>
<P>
Complementary equipment and armaments, such as electronics,
missiles are included in the 12 billion Rand (2.5 billion U.S.
dollars) total package.
</P>
<P>
Several countries are "queuing up" with proposals to supply
South Africa with corvettes, submarines, warplanes and
helicopters, South African Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils
said in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
Some Western countries, including Britain, Germany and Spain
have been trying to sell packages of weapons to the South African
National Defense Force, which complains that some key arms in use
are either obsolete or in poor condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
