<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa in Bid to Normalize Defense Ties with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 2 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Deputy
Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad will go to the United States on
Wednesday to try to normalize military relations with Washington
by solving the Armscor case, the Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Armscor, South africa's state-owned arms producer, pleaded
guilty in February this year to U.S. charges of arms smuggling in
apartheid years, and paid criminal fines totaling 12.5 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States accused Armscor of selling weapons to Middle
East containing U.S. hi-technology. But Armscor denied the
charges, saying that the technology was further advanced by
itself before the sales.
</P>
<P>
The dispute became an impediment to defense cooperation
between Washington and Pretoria, both of which are eager to
expand their weapons market share in Middle East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
A settlement was agreed on between the two sides during South
African President Nelson Mandela and his deputy Thabo Mbeki's
visits to Washington last year.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that Armscor pleaded guilty and paid fines which
will be returned to South Africa as U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
Pahad and his delegation will hold talks with U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State for Political and Military Affairs, Thomas
McNamara, the South African Foreign Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The resolution of the case would "pave the way for the rapid
normalization of defense trade relations between our two
countries," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A defense committee has been established as part of the South
Africa-U.S. Binational Commission, the statement said, and the
South African government is in the process of finalizing a
compliance program in terms of an agreement between the two
countries concerning cooperation on defense trade controls, which
was signed in Pretoria on January 24, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Pahad is also expected to meet senior State Department
officials to make preparations for the upcoming visit to South
Africa by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to visit South Africa from December 12
to 14 as part of her African tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
